Class of '56.

34
00:02:35,288 --> 00:02:38,121
How is Dickie?

35
00:02:38,191 --> 00:02:40,557
<i>We've enjoyed meeting you.</i>

36
00:02:40,627 --> 00:02:43,152
I do hope that you'll come out
and see us.

37
00:02:43,229 --> 00:02:46,221
- Thank you. That's very kind.
- Both of you.

38
00:02:46,299 --> 00:02:49,427
- Herbert?
- Yes, yes. I very much hope so.

39
00:02:49,502 --> 00:02:52,699
Of course, Dickie's idea of music is jazz.

40
00:02:52,772 --> 00:02:55,104
- Oh, dear.
- He has a saxophone.

41
00:02:55,175 --> 00:02:58,167
To my ear, jazz is just noise.

42
00:02:58,244 --> 00:03:00,337
Just an insolent noise.

43
00:03:00,413 --> 00:03:03,382
- Very nice to meet you.
- And you.

44
00:03:03,449 --> 00:03:05,383
- Sir.
- We'll see you at the shipyard.

45
00:03:05,451 --> 00:03:07,385
- I hope to.
- Good.

46
00:03:08,988 --> 00:03:11,252
I have to run!
I'm very late!

47
00:03:13,092 --> 00:03:16,084
- Ah, you were great!
- You were great.

48
00:03:16,162 --> 00:03:18,858
Darling couple, aren't they?

49
00:03:18,932 --> 00:03:21,958
Yes, they are.
Exceptional young man.

50
00:03:24,170 --> 00:03:26,434
- Thanks a lot for the jacket.
- Thanks for filling in for me.

51
00:03:26,506 --> 00:03:28,599
Take care of that wrist.
Bye, Fran.

52
00:03:36,182 --> 00:03:39,117
Believe me.
Buy I.B.M. now, before it splits.

53
00:03:39,185 --> 00:03:41,119
You'll make yourself a fortune.

54
00:03:41,187 --> 00:03:43,121
You think so?

55
00:04:19,392 --> 00:04:21,326
Sorry. Sorry.

56
00:04:22,428 --> 00:04:24,362
Sorry.

57
00:04:24,430 --> 00:04:27,797
<i>You've probably heard Dickie's
been living in Italy.</i>

58
00:04:27,867 --> 00:04:30,563
Mongibello. South of Naples.

59
00:04:30,637 --> 00:04:32,867
No kind of place at all.

60
00:04:32,939 --> 00:04:34,873
- Good morning, sir.
- Frank.

61
00:04:34,941 --> 00:04:38,274
Marge, his young lady,

62
00:04:38,344 --> 00:04:40,539
is supposedly writing
some kind of book.

63
00:04:40,613 --> 00:04:42,547
God only knows what he does.

64
00:04:42,615 --> 00:04:46,642
By all accounts, they spend the whole time
on the beach or in a sailboat.

65
00:04:46,719 --> 00:04:50,177
That's my son's talent--
spending his allowance.

66
00:04:50,256 --> 00:04:53,589
Could you ever conceive
of going to Italy, Tom?

67
00:04:53,660 --> 00:04:56,993
Persuade my son to come home?

68
00:04:58,498 --> 00:05:00,432
<i>I'd pay you...</i>

69
00:05:00,500 --> 00:05:03,435
a thousand dollars.

70
00:05:05,705 --> 00:05:09,266
Well, I have always wanted
to go to Europe, sir, but--

71
00:05:09,342 --> 00:05:13,210
Good. Now you can go for a reason.

72
00:05:28,628 --> 00:05:31,028
Count Basie.

73
00:05:31,097 --> 00:05:34,362
<i>Duke Ellington? I don't know.</i>

74
00:05:36,336 --> 00:05:38,736
I don't know.

75
00:05:40,673 --> 00:05:42,971
I don't know.

76
00:05:49,115 --> 00:05:51,413
Dizzy Gillespie.

77
00:05:51,484 --> 00:05:54,920
<i>My funny Valentine</i>

78
00:05:54,987 --> 00:05:56,852
My funny Valentine.

79
00:05:56,923 --> 00:06:01,155
<i>Sweet, funny Valentine</i>

80
00:06:01,227 --> 00:06:03,957
I don't even know
if this is a man or a woman.

81
00:06:22,115 --> 00:06:24,083
Charlie Parker?

82
00:06:24,150 --> 00:06:27,017
Charlie Parker.
I know it. It's Bird.

83
00:06:29,622 --> 00:06:31,852
Yes!

84
00:06:55,248 --> 00:06:58,342
- Here. I'll take it.
- Thanks.

85
00:06:58,418 --> 00:07:00,545
That thousand bucks should come in handy.

86
00:07:00,620 --> 00:07:02,588
- Yes, sir.
- I'll get that.

87
00:07:07,260 --> 00:07:11,890
- Thank you.
- Sir. You're gonna have a great trip.

88
00:07:11,964 --> 00:07:14,865
<i>Mr. Greenleaf is personal friends
with the Cunard people.</i>

89
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:24,342
I can tell you, the Greenleaf name
opens a lot of doors.

90
00:08:01,347 --> 00:08:05,215
- <i>Do you speak English?</i>
- <i>What you name, please?</i>

91
00:08:05,284 --> 00:08:07,548
- <i>Ripley.</i>
- <i>Follow me. No problem.</i>

92
00:08:07,620 --> 00:08:10,521
- Here, Signor Ripley.
- Okay.

93
00:08:11,691 --> 00:08:13,625
Uh, there. That one.

94
00:08:13,693 --> 00:08:15,786
- This one.
- Wait, is that all? Count them.

95
00:08:15,862 --> 00:08:18,990
<i>Attenzione.</i>
Just one suitcase, Signor Ripley?

96
00:08:19,065 --> 00:08:22,330
- <i>Si.</i>
- <i>Attenzione.</i>

97
00:08:37,783 --> 00:08:40,217
- What's your secret?
- Excuse me?

98
00:08:40,286 --> 00:08:43,414
No, it's just that--
You <i>are</i> American, aren't you?

99
00:08:43,489 --> 00:08:45,582
No, it's just that--

100
00:08:45,658 --> 00:08:50,220
I have so much luggage,
and you're so, um, streamlined.

101
00:08:50,296 --> 00:08:52,662
It's, you know, humiliating.

102
00:08:54,866 --> 00:08:56,766
I'm Meredith, by the way.

103
00:08:56,835 --> 00:09:01,397
- Hello, I'm Dickie.
- Meredith Randall.

104
00:09:01,473 --> 00:09:04,567
- Um, Dickie Greenleaf.
- Hello.

105
00:09:06,578 --> 00:09:09,570
You're not the shipping Greenleafs.

106
00:09:09,647 --> 00:09:12,013
Oh, trying not to be.

107
00:09:12,083 --> 00:09:13,744
Trying to jump ship.

108
00:09:13,818 --> 00:09:17,345
So, uh, did they put
your cases in the wrong pile?

109
00:09:17,422 --> 00:09:21,518
It's just that, uh,
you were in the "R" stand.

110
00:09:21,593 --> 00:09:25,757
I thought I saw you there.

111
00:09:25,830 --> 00:09:28,799
My father wants me back in New York.

112
00:09:28,867 --> 00:09:31,665
He builds boats.
I'd rather sail them.

113
00:09:31,736 --> 00:09:34,296
So I travel under my mother's name.

114
00:09:34,372 --> 00:09:37,773
- Which is--
- Emily.

115
00:09:37,842 --> 00:09:40,037
I'm just kidding.

116
00:09:41,346 --> 00:09:43,541
You know, the funny thing is,

117
00:09:43,615 --> 00:09:46,106
I'm not Randall either.

118
00:09:47,285 --> 00:09:49,219
I'm Logue.

119
00:09:49,287 --> 00:09:52,313
- As in--
- As in the textile Logues.

120
00:09:52,390 --> 00:09:55,188
Trying to shrug off the dress.

121
00:09:55,260 --> 00:09:57,387
- I travel under my mother's name too.
- Randall.

122
00:09:57,462 --> 00:09:59,396
Right.

123
00:09:59,464 --> 00:10:02,558
- So, Rome, Rome, Rome.
- Oh.

124
00:10:04,202 --> 00:10:07,968
- We're partners in disguise. Bye.
- Bye.

125
00:11:25,016 --> 00:11:27,280
<i>"The fianc√©e has a face."</i>

126
00:11:51,576 --> 00:11:53,601
<i>Bird.</i>

127
00:11:57,215 --> 00:11:59,809
<i>"This is my face."</i>

128
00:12:33,151 --> 00:12:36,086
<i>So I guess you didn't look
at my new chapter.</i>

129
00:12:36,154 --> 00:12:38,213
I will, Marge. I promise.

130
00:12:38,289 --> 00:12:40,223
It's just been too hot.

131
00:12:50,134 --> 00:12:52,694
If I make dinner at my place tonight,
maybe you could look at it then.

132
00:12:52,770 --> 00:12:55,102
Dickie Greenleaf?

133
00:12:55,173 --> 00:12:58,540
- Who's that?
- It's Tom. Tom Ripley.

134
00:12:58,609 --> 00:13:00,474
Tom Ripley?

135
00:13:00,545 --> 00:13:04,072
- We were at Princeton together.
- <i>Okay.</i>

136
00:13:04,148 --> 00:13:06,946
Did we know each other?

137
00:13:07,018 --> 00:13:09,680
Hello.
Well, I knew you, so...

138
00:13:09,754 --> 00:13:11,745
I suppose you must have known me.

139
00:13:13,324 --> 00:13:15,258
Princeton's like a fog.

140
00:13:15,326 --> 00:13:18,762
America's like a fog.

141
00:13:18,830 --> 00:13:22,163
This is Marge Sherwood.
Tom-- Sorry, what is it?

142
00:13:22,233 --> 00:13:23,723
- Ripley.
- <i>How do you do?</i>

143
00:13:23,801 --> 00:13:27,168
How do you do, Marge?

144
00:13:27,238 --> 00:13:29,365
- What are you doing in Mongi?
- Nothing.

145
00:13:29,440 --> 00:13:31,374
Nothing much.

146
00:13:31,442 --> 00:13:33,774
<i>Just passing through.</i>

147
00:13:33,845 --> 00:13:37,110
- Passing through?
- <i>Yeah.</i>

148
00:13:37,181 --> 00:13:39,115
You're so white.

149
00:13:41,452 --> 00:13:44,046
Did you ever see a guy so white, Marge?

150
00:13:44,122 --> 00:13:46,113
Gray, actually.

151
00:13:46,190 --> 00:13:48,681
It's just an undercoat.

152
00:13:48,760 --> 00:13:52,355
- <i>Say again?</i>
- You know, a primer.

153
00:13:54,766 --> 00:13:56,631
That's funny.

154
00:13:56,701 --> 00:13:59,602
<i>Margie likes that 'cause
she's so white too.</i>

155
00:13:59,670 --> 00:14:01,763
Yes, I do, and you're not funny.

156
00:14:01,839 --> 00:14:03,773
You should come and have lunch with us
before you go.

157
00:14:03,841 --> 00:14:06,605
- Yes, Dickie?
- <i>Sure, anytime.</i>

158
00:14:06,677 --> 00:14:09,111
Well,

159
00:14:09,180 --> 00:14:11,114
coincidence.

160
00:14:15,553 --> 00:14:17,851
I don't remember him.

161
00:14:17,922 --> 00:14:20,059
That's so funny.

162
00:14:26,098 --> 00:14:28,328
Silvana! Hey!

163
00:14:29,868 --> 00:14:32,302
I've been looking all over for you.

164
00:14:32,371 --> 00:14:34,236
<i>Where've you been hiding?</i>

165
00:14:34,306 --> 00:14:37,207
Today you're looking for me.
Where've you been the rest of the week?

166
00:14:37,276 --> 00:14:40,643
You're always working.
Come on. Get on.

167
00:14:40,712 --> 00:14:43,510
<i>With the American girl?</i>

168
00:14:43,582 --> 00:14:45,516
- Hold on to me.
- I hate you.

169
00:14:45,584 --> 00:14:49,247
- <i>Huh?</i>
- <i>I hate you!</i>

170
00:14:50,923 --> 00:14:52,857
<i>Did you suddenly forget where I lived?</i>

171
00:14:52,925 --> 00:14:55,086
I know. I'm late. I'm a swine.

172
00:14:55,160 --> 00:14:57,094
- It's 4:00.
- I just woke up.

173
00:14:57,162 --> 00:14:59,630
- Ohh.
- I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

174
00:14:59,698 --> 00:15:02,394
- You just woke up.
- Fausto and I took the boat out.

175
00:15:02,468 --> 00:15:06,097
We were fishing, and then it was dawn,
and we caught absolutely nothing.

176
00:15:06,171 --> 00:15:10,335
Mmm, yes, well,
we ate everything without you.

177
00:15:10,409 --> 00:15:12,536
- We?
- Yes.

178
00:15:12,611 --> 00:15:15,512
- Tom Ripley's here.
- Who?

179
00:15:17,583 --> 00:15:20,814
- Tom. Hello.
- <i>Hi.</i>

180
00:15:20,886 --> 00:15:23,377
- Hello.
- How are you? Thought you'd disappeared.

181
00:15:23,455 --> 00:15:26,390
- We were gonna send out a search party.
- <i>No.</i>

182
00:15:26,458 --> 00:15:30,656
- No, still here.
- Tom was telling me about his journey.

183
00:15:30,729 --> 00:15:34,722
<i>Made me laugh so hard
I almost got a nosebleed.</i>

184
00:15:34,800 --> 00:15:38,395
- Is that good?
- Shut up.

185
00:15:38,470 --> 00:15:41,405
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

186
00:15:41,473 --> 00:15:44,101
I'm despicable. But I love you.

187
00:15:44,176 --> 00:15:47,111
- <i>Do you love me? Do you love me?</i>
- I'm intruding.

188
00:15:47,179 --> 00:15:49,670
Can you mix a martini?

189
00:15:51,884 --> 00:15:55,012
- Sure.
- I'll do it.

190
00:15:55,087 --> 00:15:58,022
- Ohh.
- I make a fabulous martini.

191
00:16:02,828 --> 00:16:06,195
Everybody should have one talent.
What's yours?

192
00:16:06,265 --> 00:16:08,358
Forging signatures,

193
00:16:08,433 --> 00:16:11,493
telling lies,
impersonating practically anybody.

194
00:16:11,570 --> 00:16:15,666
That's three.
Nobody should have more than one talent.

195
00:16:16,775 --> 00:16:19,005
<i>Okay, do an impression.</i>

196
00:16:19,077 --> 00:16:21,602
- Now?
- Yeah.

197
00:16:21,680 --> 00:16:24,774
The only talent my son has...

198
00:16:24,850 --> 00:16:27,284
<i>is for cashing his allowance.</i>

199
00:16:29,488 --> 00:16:31,820
- What?
- Oh, I like to sail.

200
00:16:31,890 --> 00:16:33,790
Believe me, I love to sail.

201
00:16:33,859 --> 00:16:35,850
- Instead, I make boats.
- <i>Stop!</i>

202
00:16:35,928 --> 00:16:38,294
- <i>Other people sail them.</i>
- It's too much!

203
00:16:38,363 --> 00:16:40,354
You're making all the hairs
on my neck stand up.

204
00:16:40,432 --> 00:16:43,833
Oh, yes. Jazz.
Oh, jazz. Let's face it.

205
00:16:43,902 --> 00:16:47,463
It's just, uh--
It's just insolent noise.

206
00:16:47,539 --> 00:16:49,530
I feel like he's here.

207
00:16:49,608 --> 00:16:53,044
- Horrible, like the old bastard's here.
- Good.

208
00:16:53,111 --> 00:16:54,976
That's brilliant.

209
00:16:55,047 --> 00:16:57,743
Brilliant!
How do you know him?

210
00:16:57,816 --> 00:16:59,613
Oh, I met him in New York.

211
00:16:59,685 --> 00:17:01,915
Marge!
Marge, this is scary.

212
00:17:01,987 --> 00:17:04,285
You've got to hear this.
Meet my father,

213
00:17:04,356 --> 00:17:06,551
Herbert Richard Greenleaf I.

214
00:17:06,625 --> 00:17:10,527
Pleasure to meet you.
Dickie's made a fine catch.

215
00:17:10,596 --> 00:17:13,121
- Uncanny!
- I know Emily thinks so.

216
00:17:13,198 --> 00:17:15,462
- I don't get it.
- It's uncanny.

217
00:17:15,534 --> 00:17:18,662
Could you ever conceive
of going to Italy, Tom,

218
00:17:18,737 --> 00:17:21,672
<i>and, uh, bringing him back?</i>

219
00:17:21,740 --> 00:17:23,935
- What?
- I'd pay you.

220
00:17:24,009 --> 00:17:25,943
If you would go to Italy,

221
00:17:26,011 --> 00:17:29,970
persuade my son to come home,
I'd pay you a thousand dollars.

222
00:17:32,651 --> 00:17:34,642
<i>I'm never going back.</i>

223
00:17:34,720 --> 00:17:37,416
To actually hire somebody
to come all the way here...

224
00:17:37,489 --> 00:17:39,423
to drag me back home--

225
00:17:39,491 --> 00:17:41,618
Got to be a little insane,
doesn't he?

226
00:17:41,693 --> 00:17:44,218
<i>Ciao,</i> Fausto.

227
00:17:48,233 --> 00:17:50,701
- This is Tom.
- <i>Ciao,</i> Tom.

228
00:17:52,971 --> 00:17:55,496
- I'm never going back.
- No, I think--

229
00:17:55,574 --> 00:17:57,542
Your mother, her illness,
I think that's--

230
00:17:57,609 --> 00:18:00,703
It's got nothing to do
with my mother.

231
00:18:00,779 --> 00:18:04,442
She's had leukem--
This is what makes me boil about him.

232
00:18:04,516 --> 00:18:08,111
He wants me back.
He wants me back.

233
00:18:08,186 --> 00:18:10,552
- It's got nothing to do with my mother.
- Look, I don't know--

234
00:18:10,622 --> 00:18:12,556
Go back.
Go back to New York.

235
00:18:12,624 --> 00:18:14,683
Or call him,
if you can find a telephone that works,

236
00:18:14,760 --> 00:18:19,298
and tell him wild horses wouldn't drag me
back to him or his shipyard.

237
00:18:21,733 --> 00:18:24,759
- Hi, Tom.
- <i>Hi.</i>

238
00:18:24,836 --> 00:18:27,134
Marge, Tom's saying good-bye.

239
00:18:27,205 --> 00:18:29,264
Oh, I'll come down.

240
00:18:30,776 --> 00:18:33,176
So, uh, did you speak to my father?

241
00:18:33,245 --> 00:18:35,475
Oh, you were right...
about the telephones.

242
00:18:35,547 --> 00:18:37,481
- <i>I told you.</i>
