You must be very cold.
Uh, Signor Greenleaf, yes?

713
00:59:11,378 --> 00:59:13,312
No. I'm--

714
01:00:23,050 --> 01:00:26,542
Hello, Marge.

715
01:00:26,620 --> 01:00:29,248
Tom!

716
01:00:29,322 --> 01:00:31,381
You startled me!

717
01:00:31,458 --> 01:00:34,655
- Sorry. How are you?
- <i>You're back!</i>

718
01:00:34,728 --> 01:00:37,196
- <i>Your book going well?</i>
- Yes.

719
01:00:37,264 --> 01:00:40,290
I'm on a good streak, thank you.

720
01:00:40,367 --> 01:00:43,962
I was just... looking at you.
So quiet.

721
01:00:44,037 --> 01:00:46,972
Where's Dickie?

722
01:00:50,277 --> 01:00:53,303
I think he's planning
on staying in Rome for a few days.

723
01:00:53,380 --> 01:00:57,146
Rome? Ahh.
Did he say why?

724
01:00:57,217 --> 01:01:00,209
I don't understand Dickie.
Your guess is as good as mine.

725
01:01:00,287 --> 01:01:02,255
What does that mean?

726
01:01:02,322 --> 01:01:06,850
Oh, one day I'm invited skiing,
the next day I'm not.

727
01:01:09,029 --> 01:01:13,295
<i>One day, we're one family,
then the next day he wants to be alone.</i>

728
01:01:13,366 --> 01:01:15,300
<i>You tell me.</i>

729
01:01:15,368 --> 01:01:17,928
Is that what he said?
He wants to be alone?

730
01:01:18,004 --> 01:01:22,441
He was thinking of you.
He asked me to deliver this.

731
01:01:22,509 --> 01:01:25,876
Thank you.

732
01:01:25,946 --> 01:01:28,005
<i>He knows I love this.</i>

733
01:01:29,783 --> 01:01:32,843
- But why it couldn't have waited. I--
- <i>Errand number one.</i>

734
01:01:32,919 --> 01:01:35,444
deliver Marge's perfume.

735
01:01:35,522 --> 01:01:38,082
Errand number two:

736
01:01:38,158 --> 01:01:41,355
pack some clothes
and his precious saxophone.

737
01:01:42,996 --> 01:01:44,964
How long is he staying for?

738
01:01:45,031 --> 01:01:48,467
Search me.
I guess we're abandoned.

739
01:02:14,828 --> 01:02:17,194
Goddamn it!

740
01:02:18,565 --> 01:02:20,499
Are you okay?

741
01:02:31,044 --> 01:02:34,377
<i>There was a letter from Dickie
in with my perfume.</i>

742
01:02:36,483 --> 01:02:40,146
You realize it's more
than just a few days.

743
01:02:40,220 --> 01:02:44,213
He's thinking of moving to Rome.

744
01:02:44,291 --> 01:02:46,691
<i>The thing is,</i>

745
01:02:46,760 --> 01:02:49,456
the night before he left, we--

746
01:02:49,529 --> 01:02:51,622
we talked about moving together...

747
01:02:53,333 --> 01:02:55,426
<i>somewhere north,</i>
<i>and I suppose I...</i>

748
01:02:58,038 --> 01:03:01,303
put some pressure on him
about getting married.

749
01:03:03,310 --> 01:03:05,471
I just--

750
01:03:07,480 --> 01:03:09,778
I just might have scared him off.

751
01:03:15,422 --> 01:03:18,084
There's a side to him...

752
01:03:18,158 --> 01:03:21,491
when our heads are on the pillow...

753
01:03:21,561 --> 01:03:24,928
I know no one else sees 
that's so tender.

754
01:03:26,967 --> 01:03:30,300
I think I should come with you to Rome
and confront him.

755
01:03:36,610 --> 01:03:39,511
He hates being confronted.

756
01:03:41,281 --> 01:03:43,550
I think you're right.

757
01:03:52,492 --> 01:03:54,653
<i>Grazie.</i> Checking in.

758
01:04:03,069 --> 01:04:05,003
Checking in.

759
01:04:05,071 --> 01:04:09,201
- Signor Ripley?
- It's me.

760
01:04:11,377 --> 01:04:14,471
Signor Greenleaf.

761
01:04:14,547 --> 01:04:17,038
Of course. Welcome back.

762
01:04:17,116 --> 01:04:19,516
Thank you.

763
01:04:36,970 --> 01:04:38,904
<i>Pronto?</i>

764
01:04:38,972 --> 01:04:42,339
Yes, I'd like to telephone
the Hotel Goldoni.

765
01:04:42,408 --> 01:04:47,004
- Si, <i>signor.</i>
- <i>I want to speak to Thomas Ripley.</i>

766
01:04:47,080 --> 01:04:50,015
- <i>Ripley?</i> Subito.
- Yes. <i>Grazie.</i>

767
01:05:01,991 --> 01:05:02,985
<i>Pronto.</i>

768
01:05:03,062 --> 01:05:04,996
<i>Signor Greenleaf,
Signor Ripley's not there.</i>

769
01:05:05,064 --> 01:05:07,191
- He's not there?
- <i>No, signor.</i>

770
01:05:07,266 --> 01:05:09,996
Well, I would like
to leave a message.

771
01:05:10,069 --> 01:05:12,333
- He's not there? I'll leave a message.
- <i>No, signor.</i>

772
01:05:12,405 --> 01:05:14,532
- Got your call.
- <i>Got your call.</i>

773
01:05:14,607 --> 01:05:16,541
- Dinner tonight...
- <i>Dinner tonight...</i>

774
01:05:16,609 --> 01:05:18,543
- sounds fine.
- <i>sounds fine.</i>

775
01:05:18,611 --> 01:05:22,103
- Ripley. Ripley.
- <i>Ripley.</i>

776
01:05:22,181 --> 01:05:25,673
- Dickie Greenleaf.
- <i>Dickie Greenleaf.</i>

777
01:05:25,752 --> 01:05:28,744
- Yes. Greenleaf.
- <i>Greenleaf.</i>

778
01:05:28,821 --> 01:05:30,948
At the Grand.

779
01:05:31,024 --> 01:05:34,460
<i>And I'd like to have
this wallet embossed.</i>

780
01:05:34,527 --> 01:05:36,461
I don't know the word in Italian.

781
01:05:36,529 --> 01:05:38,554
Embossed.
Of course, Signor Greenleaf.

782
01:05:38,631 --> 01:05:40,599
Thank you.

783
01:05:44,337 --> 01:05:48,034
Dickie! It's--

784
01:05:51,110 --> 01:05:53,044
- Oh, my gosh.
- Meredith.

785
01:05:53,112 --> 01:05:55,046
- <i>Ciao!</i>
- <i>Ciao.</i> Come in. Come in.

786
01:05:55,114 --> 01:05:57,776
But you're going skiing
with those Yankees, aren't you?

787
01:05:57,850 --> 01:06:02,514
- What?
- At Christmas. To Cortina.

788
01:06:02,588 --> 01:06:04,556
- With Freddie Miles.
- How did you know that?

789
01:06:04,624 --> 01:06:08,651
Oh! Everybody knows Freddie Miles.

790
01:06:11,364 --> 01:06:13,355
Is Freddie in Rome?

791
01:06:13,433 --> 01:06:15,367
- Now?
- Yeah.

792
01:06:15,435 --> 01:06:17,801
Oh, I don't think so.

793
01:06:17,870 --> 01:06:22,273
But I-- But I've met him, of course, 
and we've chatted.

794
01:06:22,341 --> 01:06:25,970
And I know about you...

795
01:06:26,045 --> 01:06:28,639
and Marge in Mongi.

796
01:06:28,715 --> 01:06:31,912
What an unreliable rat you are.

797
01:06:31,984 --> 01:06:34,248
Well, Freddie said you were a rat.

798
01:06:34,320 --> 01:06:36,618
And I thought to myself,

799
01:06:36,689 --> 01:06:39,817
"Ah, now I know why he travels under 'R.'"

800
01:06:39,892 --> 01:06:42,224
I've left Marge, Meredith.

801
01:06:42,295 --> 01:06:44,525
And Mongi.

802
01:06:44,597 --> 01:06:47,862
- So the rat's here in Rome.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

803
01:06:47,934 --> 01:06:51,062
Oh, don't be sorry, no.
I've never been happier.

804
01:06:51,137 --> 01:06:54,436
I-- I feel like
I've been handed a new life.

805
01:06:54,507 --> 01:06:58,409
The truth is that if you've had money
your entire life,

806
01:06:58,478 --> 01:07:01,777
either you despise it,
which we do-- agreed?

807
01:07:01,848 --> 01:07:04,817
You're only truly comfortable
around other people...

808
01:07:04,884 --> 01:07:07,944
who have it and despise it.

809
01:07:08,020 --> 01:07:09,954
I know.

810
01:07:11,457 --> 01:07:14,085
I've never admitted that to anyone.

811
01:07:19,632 --> 01:07:22,897
<i>Because my friend Mr. Greenleaf,
Signor Greenleaf and I,</i>

812
01:07:22,969 --> 01:07:24,903
<i>are on a little spending spree.</i>

813
01:07:24,971 --> 01:07:28,930
- <i>I see.</i>
- <i>We're behaving very badly.</i>

814
01:07:29,008 --> 01:07:33,468
<i>Oh, I love Italian money. So dark.
Doesn't make you feel guilty.</i>

815
01:07:33,546 --> 01:07:35,480
- <i>Gr-r-razie.</i>
- Thank you.

816
01:07:46,058 --> 01:07:49,585
I don't want too many large bills.
No one will change them.

817
01:07:49,662 --> 01:07:51,755
<i>Tutto bene,</i> Signor Greenleaf.

818
01:08:07,580 --> 01:08:11,243
- I really like this too.
- I think I'm having that too.

819
01:08:17,590 --> 01:08:20,081
Tomorrow.

820
01:08:24,897 --> 01:08:27,388
- <i>Arrivederci.</i>
- <i>Arrivederci.</i> Oops!

821
01:08:28,601 --> 01:08:30,535
- Ciao.
- Ciao.

822
01:08:36,042 --> 01:08:40,445
I know you're a jazz fiend,
but do you absolutely hate the opera?

823
01:08:43,683 --> 01:08:46,584
I've-- I've...

824
01:08:46,652 --> 01:08:50,281
been trying to give
my tickets away.

825
01:08:50,356 --> 01:08:54,793
It's tomorrow. But if you 
were prepared to be dragged--

826
01:08:56,295 --> 01:08:58,490
You could drag me.

827
01:10:46,806 --> 01:10:50,503
Feodor Chaliapin.
It's the whole Russian baritone.

828
01:10:50,576 --> 01:10:53,977
Thank you so much
for inviting me tonight.

829
01:10:54,046 --> 01:10:57,880
Can you bear it?
We hear you are a friend of Freddie's.

830
01:10:57,950 --> 01:11:01,147
He has "I hate opera"
tattooed on his chest.

831
01:11:01,220 --> 01:11:03,711
There's room for a whole libretto
on Freddie's chest.

832
01:11:05,825 --> 01:11:08,157
I'm sure we've met before.

833
01:11:08,227 --> 01:11:11,162
I was sure we'd met before.
Weren't you, Ted?

834
01:11:11,230 --> 01:11:13,255
Dick is Herbert Greenleaf's boy.

835
01:11:13,332 --> 01:11:15,892
- I know.
- Yes, I think we have.

836
01:11:15,968 --> 01:11:20,064
One minute you people are children,
and the next you're getting tattooed.

837
01:11:22,041 --> 01:11:24,601
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

838
01:11:26,712 --> 01:11:28,646
Cheers.

839
01:11:32,952 --> 01:11:35,386
- Excuse me.
- <i>Prego.</i>

840
01:11:35,454 --> 01:11:37,820
Oh! Excuse me.

841
01:11:37,890 --> 01:11:40,120
- Hello.
- Hello.

842
01:11:41,627 --> 01:11:43,561
- Tom!
- Marge!

843
01:11:43,629 --> 01:11:46,757
How are you?
What are you doing in Rome?

844
01:11:46,832 --> 01:11:50,495
- Is he here? Are you with Dickie?
- No. Um, no.

845
01:11:50,570 --> 01:11:53,630
Um, hello.
Um, I'm Tom Ripley.

846
01:11:53,706 --> 01:11:56,106
Peter Smith-Kingsley. I've heard
all about you from Marge and Dickie.

847
01:11:56,175 --> 01:11:59,144
- Ditto.
- No-No glasses.

848
01:11:59,211 --> 01:12:02,044
So, where are you hiding him?
He's impossible, isn't he?

849
01:12:02,114 --> 01:12:04,241
Is he really not here?

850
01:12:04,317 --> 01:12:07,980
Marge, you know Dickie has
"I hate opera" tattooed on his chest.

851
01:12:08,054 --> 01:12:11,080
- I thought you were going to Venice.
- Yes, what happened with that?

852
01:12:11,157 --> 01:12:13,091
I heard you were desperate to come.

853
01:12:13,159 --> 01:12:15,150
I was rather looking forward
to rowing you around.

854
01:12:15,227 --> 01:12:18,924
I am. I really am.

855
01:12:18,998 --> 01:12:22,229
I've been traveling,
and I just can't seem to get that far north.

856
01:12:22,301 --> 01:12:24,166
Well, you should hurry,
before we sink.

857
01:12:24,236 --> 01:12:27,330
<i>Look, let me give you
the telephone number.</i>

858
01:12:27,406 --> 01:12:30,273
There. Oh, look.
There's Meredith.

859
01:12:30,343 --> 01:12:33,608
<i>Meredith. What's her name, Marge?
The textile people.</i>

860
01:12:33,679 --> 01:12:37,171
Um, come on. Some of us
spent Christmas at her house.

861
01:12:37,249 --> 01:12:40,980
I don't know her.

862
01:12:41,053 --> 01:12:44,853
He hasn't called.
He's hardly written.

863
01:12:44,924 --> 01:12:47,051
Just these cryptic notes, you know?

864
01:12:47,126 --> 01:12:49,151
You don't just dump people.

865
01:12:49,228 --> 01:12:52,857
<i>Look, will we see you later,
or are you with people?</i>

866
01:12:52,932 --> 01:12:55,924
- Uh, I can't later.
- Well, how about tomorrow?

867
01:12:56,002 --> 01:12:57,936
<i>Yes, uh, maybe in the morning?</i>

868
01:12:58,004 --> 01:13:01,667
Do you know Cafe Dinelli
at the Piazza di Spagna?

869
01:13:01,741 --> 01:13:05,233
- I know the Piazza. What time?
- 10:30?

870
01:13:05,311 --> 01:13:07,541
- We'll be there.
- Okay.

871
01:13:07,613 --> 01:13:09,638
So I'll see you in the morning, Marge?

872
01:13:09,715 --> 01:13:12,775
<i>10:30? Very nice to meet you.</i>

873
01:13:12,852 --> 01:13:14,911
<i>And you.</i>

874
01:13:17,790 --> 01:13:19,655
Come on.

875
01:13:19,725 --> 01:13:23,661
Come on.
Let's go back in.

876
01:13:29,568 --> 01:13:32,662
I don't understand 
why Tom's still in Rome.

877
01:13:32,738 --> 01:13:37,004
- Let's go.
- I thought you were enjoying yourself.

878
01:13:37,076 --> 01:13:39,374
Let's take a <i>carrozza</i>
and look at the moon.

879
01:13:39,445 --> 01:13:41,379
Are you crazy?
It's freezing out there.

880
01:13:41,447 --> 01:13:44,280
Come on. I need to talk to you.
Just the two of us.

881
01:13:44,350 --> 01:13:46,443
<i>Okay.</i>

882
01:13:50,222 --> 01:13:52,713
Don't worry, please.

883
01:13:52,792 --> 01:13:55,659
Don't worry.

884
01:13:55,728 --> 01:13:59,824
You're such a pal to understand. I--

885
01:13:59,899 --> 01:14:02,026
It's like Marge is here right now.
I look at you,

886
01:14:02,101 --> 01:14:04,194
<i>and I see her face.</i>

887
01:14:04,270 --> 01:14:07,034
And I can't-- No matter
what I'm feeling towards you--

888
01:14:07,106 --> 01:14:12,476
No. I absolutely... understand. 
Of c--

889
01:14:12,545 --> 01:14:16,037
Otherwise, you'd be fighting me off.

890
01:14:16,115 --> 01:14:18,083
Beating you away.

891
01:14:56,756 --> 01:14:59,987
But will you meet me tomorrow?

892
01:15:00,059 --> 01:15:03,290
Just to say good-bye properly,
you know, in the daylight,

893
01:15:03,362 --> 01:15:05,523
so it's not just this.

894
01:15:05,598 --> 01:15:08,362
Of course. Meredith, I'm sorry.
Of course I'll meet you.

895
01:15:08,434 --> 01:15:13,667
You should always save pain for daylight.

896
01:15:13,739 --> 01:15:17,038
Why don't we have coffee
in the morning at Dinelli's?

897
01:15:17,109 --> 01:15:19,270
Uh, by the Spanish Steps.

898
01:15:19,345 --> 01:15:21,176
Exactly. 10:30?

899
01:15:23,916 --> 01:15:26,510
- 10:15.
- Okay.

900
01:15:26,585 --> 01:15:28,746
Okay.

901
01:16:20,005 --> 01:16:22,337
- <i>Grazie.</i>
- Peter?

902
01:16:22,407 --> 01:16:25,934
<i>Hello. It's Meredith Logue.</i>

903
01:16:26,011 --> 01:16:28,673
<i>Of course it is.
Meredith, hello. Sorry.</i>

904
01:16:28,747 --> 01:16:31,807
- I was half asleep. How are you?
- How are you?

905
01:16:31,883 --> 01:16:34,249
This is Marge Sherwood.
Meredith Logue.

906
01:16:34,319 --> 01:16:37,345
How do you do?

907
01:16:37,422 --> 01:16:40,755
<i>Do join us, won't you?
We're just waiting for a friend.</i>

908
01:16:40,825 --> 01:16:43,555
I-- I won't, actually.
I think there's--

909
01:16:43,628 --> 01:16:46,222
- Did we see you at the opera last night?
- Uh--

910
01:16:46,297 --> 01:16:49,027
Are you waiting for Dickie?

911
01:16:49,100 --> 01:16:53,230
Dickie? Do you-- Do you--
Do you know Dickie?

912
01:16:53,304 --> 01:16:56,467
You were at the opera.
Oh, that explains-- Yes, I was there.

913
01:16:56,541 --> 01:17:00,068
I was there with Dickie.

914
01:17:01,146 --> 01:17:03,910
I knew it.

915
01:17:03,982 --> 01:17:06,212
<i>I told you.</i>

916
01:17:08,286 --> 01:17:12,814
Marge, I don't know you,
so I've got no right to--

917
01:17:12,891 --> 01:17:16,088
Dickie loves you.
He's-- Well--

918
01:17:16,161 --> 01:17:19,324
I think you'll find
he's on his way home to you.

919
01:17:19,397 --> 01:17:23,424
Well, how-how-how
would you know that?

920
01:17:24,669 --> 01:17:27,229
He... told me everything.

921
01:17:27,305 --> 01:17:32,242
No, I was supposed to meet him
15 minutes ago, so, uh,

922
01:17:32,310 --> 01:17:34,744
I'm gonna go now, I think.

923
01:17:37,048 --> 01:17:39,107
God, unless he meant us to meet.

924
01:17:39,184 --> 01:17:41,379
<i>That'd be a little cruel,
wouldn't it?</i>

925
01:17:41,453 --> 01:17:43,853
<i>No, no, we're meeting another friend.</i>

926
01:17:43,922 --> 01:17:46,755
- Tom Ripley.
- Do you know Tom Ripley?

927
01:17:46,825 --> 01:17:51,660
No, no. I've heard about him,
of course, but I didn't meet him, no.

928
01:17:51,729 --> 01:17:54,197
Not for me. No, <i>grazie.</i>

929
01:17:59,537 --> 01:18:02,472
Hope I didn't complicate matters.

930
01:18:02,540 --> 01:18:07,876
God, nothing, nothing...
untoward happened.

931
01:18:07,946 --> 01:18:12,178
<i>No, there is nothing to prevent you
from welcoming him back,</i>

932
01:18:12,250 --> 01:18:14,184
from marrying him.

933
01:18:18,723 --> 01:18:21,453
Good-bye.
I'm happy to put a face to a name.

934
01:18:21,526 --> 01:18:24,017
Good-bye, Peter.
Please, don't get up.

935
01:18:44,549 --> 01:18:47,677
Now I don't know what to think.
Do you think he's coming back?

936
01:18:49,287 --> 01:18:52,688
Sorry. Sorry.
Had to renew my papers.

937
01:18:52,757 --> 01:18:55,089
Never one stamp when they
can make you line up for three.

938
01:18:55,160 --> 01:18:57,287
- Have you been waiting long?
- Not at all.

939
01:18:57,362 --> 01:19:00,092
- Morning, Tom.
- Hi. Sorry.

940
01:19:00,165 --> 01:19:02,099
<i>You okay? You look like
you've seen a ghost.</i>

941
01:19:02,167 --> 01:19:04,863
Dickie was at the opera last night.

942
01:19:04,936 --> 01:19:08,269
I don't believe that. Uh--
Wild horses couldn't drag Dickie--

943
01:19:08,339 --> 01:19:10,637
Well, he was there with someone,
you know,

944
01:19:10,708 --> 01:19:13,199
so I suppose she must have dragged him.

945
01:19:13,278 --> 01:19:16,111
It's not fair.

946
01:19:16,181 --> 01:19:20,345
I think I'm going back to Mongi.
I think Dickie's coming home.

947
01:19:20,418 --> 01:19:23,046
Really? I-- Well, that's just swell.

948
01:19:23,121 --> 01:19:25,783
No, you know, you're way ahead of me.
Great.

949
01:19:25,857 --> 01:19:27,825
That was rather moving
when I heard-- I'm sorry.

950
01:19:27,892 --> 01:19:30,292
Meredith is the American girl
I saw at the opera last night.

951
01:19:30,361 --> 01:19:34,457
- <i>She's been seeing something of Dickie.</i>
- Oh, my God.

952
01:19:34,532 --> 01:19:37,990
<i>But the point is, Dickie--
and we all know this.</i>

953
01:19:38,069 --> 01:19:41,732
Dickie loves Marge.
And he misses her.

954
01:19:41,806 --> 01:19:44,570
I feel guilty.
Marge doesn't understand this,

955
01:19:44,642 --> 01:19:47,509
but whenever Dickie does something,
I feel guilty.

956
01:19:47,579 --> 01:19:49,877
As if that makes sense.

957
01:21:13,131 --> 01:21:15,065
<i>Dickie.</i>

958
01:21:16,768 --> 01:21:19,134
<i>Dickie, come on. It's me.</i>

959
01:21:21,573 --> 01:21:23,507
It's Freddie. Let me in.

960
01:21:26,544 --> 01:21:28,478
<i>Dickie.</i>

961
01:21:33,752 --> 01:21:36,585
Hello, Freddie. It's Tom.

962
01:21:37,656 --> 01:21:40,591
<i>Um, where's Dickie?</i>

963
01:21:40,659 --> 01:21:42,593
How are you?

964
01:21:42,661 --> 01:21:45,721
I'm good. Uh, yes, thank you.
He's gone. He went to dinner.

965
01:21:45,797 --> 01:21:50,166
- He's at Otello's. You know Otello's?
- No, no, no.

966
01:21:50,235 --> 01:21:53,033
I-I don't think he's at dinner
at 6:30 p.m.

967
01:21:53,104 --> 01:21:56,403
If you said he was still at lunch,
maybe I'd believe you.

968
01:21:56,474 --> 01:22:00,069
You know? Incredible.

969
01:22:00,145 --> 01:22:04,081
I mean, the guy just, you know,
disappeared off the face of the earth.

970
01:22:06,251 --> 01:22:08,185
I guess.

971
01:22:09,320 --> 01:22:12,380
The landlady, as far as I could tell--

972
01:22:12,457 --> 01:22:16,257
<i>The landlady said
he was here right now.</i>

973
01:22:16,327 --> 01:22:18,557
Search the place.

974
01:22:18,630 --> 01:22:22,031
I-I just don't-- I don't know why
you'd imagine that Dickie would hide from you.

975
01:22:22,100 --> 01:22:24,034
Because he's been hiding from me.

976
01:22:26,204 --> 01:22:30,038
- <i>What happened at Christmas?</i>
- What about Christmas?

977
01:22:30,108 --> 01:22:33,236
<i>He was supposed to come skiing.
I didn't get a cable...</i>

978
01:22:33,311 --> 01:22:35,541
or a call or a little note or a--

979
01:22:35,613 --> 01:22:40,141
<i>Frankly, a fart.</i>

980
01:22:40,218 --> 01:22:42,482
Well, he's been very involved
with his music.

981
01:22:42,554 --> 01:22:46,752
Um, I think his theory... is...

982
01:22:46,825 --> 01:22:51,421
that you have to go into a cocoon,
uh, before you can be a butterfly.

983
01:22:51,496 --> 01:22:54,056
Which is horseshit.

984
01:22:54,132 --> 01:22:57,590
You hear him play this thing?
Well, he can't.

985
01:23:00,472 --> 01:23:02,565
How did you find him?

986
01:23:02,640 --> 01:23:05,632
<i>It's such an out-of-the-way apartment.
Can I fix you a drink?</i>

987
01:23:05,710 --> 01:23:08,679
No, thanks.
At the American Express.

988
01:23:12,117 --> 01:23:14,551
Some kid.

989
01:23:20,058 --> 01:23:22,993
Are you living here?

990
01:23:23,061 --> 01:23:26,155
No, no. I'm staying here
for a few days.

991
01:23:28,833 --> 01:23:31,495
But--

992
01:23:31,569 --> 01:23:35,266
It's a new piano.
Probably shouldn't--

993
01:23:39,811 --> 01:23:42,405
Probably shouldn't--

994
01:23:45,350 --> 01:23:49,116
Did this place come furnished?

995
01:23:49,187 --> 01:23:52,384
<i>It doesn't look like Dickie's, uh--</i>

996
01:23:52,457 --> 01:23:55,551
It's really horrible, isn't it?

997
01:23:57,128 --> 01:24:00,620
<i>It's so, uh, bourgeois.</i>

998
01:24:10,141 --> 01:24:12,336
Oh, that's a, uh--
You should-- Watch that.

999
01:24:12,410 --> 01:24:15,538
Excuse-- Excuse me.

1000
01:24:15,613 --> 01:24:17,547
Excuse me.

1001
01:24:20,552 --> 01:24:25,216
In fact, the only thing that looks
like Dickie... is you.

1002
01:24:25,290 --> 01:24:27,315
- Hardly.
- Hmm.

1003
01:24:29,260 --> 01:24:31,990
Have you done something to your hair?

1004
01:24:32,063 --> 01:24:34,088
Is there something
you'd like to say, Freddie?

1005
01:24:34,165 --> 01:24:36,565
- What?
- You have something you'd like to say?

1006
01:24:36,634 --> 01:24:39,000
I think I'm saying it.

1007
01:24:40,438 --> 01:24:43,601
<i>Something's going on.</i>

1008
01:24:43,675 --> 01:24:46,508
Either he's converted to Christianity,

1009
01:24:47,712 --> 01:24:49,646
or there's something else.

1010
01:24:51,082 --> 01:24:53,209
Well, I would suggest you
ask Dickie that yourself.

1011
01:24:53,284 --> 01:24:56,185
Otello's is on della Croce
just off the Corso.

1012
01:24:56,254 --> 01:24:59,746
<i>Is it on della Croce
just off the Corso?</i>

1013
01:25:01,826 --> 01:25:06,058
<i>Sure. You're a quick study,
aren't you?</i>

1014
01:25:06,130 --> 01:25:08,064
Last time you didn't know
you ass from your elbow.

1015
01:25:08,132 --> 01:25:10,566
Now you're giving me directions.

1016
01:25:10,635 --> 01:25:14,401
<i>That's not fair. You probably
do know your ass from your elbow.</i>

1017
01:25:17,308 --> 01:25:19,242
I'll see you.

1018
01:25:31,389 --> 01:25:33,983
<i>No Dickie Greenleaf. Thomas Ripley.</i>

1019
01:25:34,058 --> 01:25:37,459
<i>Si.</i>

1020
01:25:42,667 --> 01:25:44,658
<i>Ciao,</i> Dickie.

1021
01:25:49,140 --> 01:25:51,608
Dickie doesn't play the piano.

1022
01:25:53,144 --> 01:25:55,078
<i>Tommy.</i>

1023
01:25:55,146 --> 01:25:57,080
<i>Tommy!</i>

1024
01:26:37,622 --> 01:26:40,420
Oh! You're making me laugh.

1025
01:26:40,491 --> 01:26:44,291
No. You're just so drunk.
Oh. You're just--

1026
01:26:44,362 --> 01:26:47,695
What can you do, eh?
You should see my other friends.

1027
01:26:47,765 --> 01:26:50,165
<i>What can you do?</i>

1028
01:26:50,234 --> 01:26:53,465
Yes. Such a pig.

1029
01:26:56,975 --> 01:27:02,242
Hey, if I'm drunk,
think what her husband's saying.

1030
01:27:49,693 --> 01:27:52,059
- <i>La polizia.</i>
- Dickie Greenleaf?

1031
01:27:52,129 --> 01:27:55,155
- Yes.
- Inspector Roverini.

1032
01:27:55,232 --> 01:27:57,257
- Can we come in?
- Please.

1033
01:28:04,975 --> 01:28:07,307
It's a terrible shock, huh?

1034
01:28:07,378 --> 01:28:11,075
W-What time did Signor Miles
leave yesterday?

1035
01:28:11,148 --> 01:28:15,175
Oh, um, I can't be certain exactly. I--

1036
01:28:15,252 --> 01:28:17,186
8:00, 9:00.

1037
01:28:20,057 --> 01:28:24,460
We'd both taken on, uh,
far too many drinks.

1038
01:28:24,528 --> 01:28:29,090
But it was dark. It was certainly dark
when I-- when I walked him to his car.

1039
01:28:29,166 --> 01:28:32,135
So he drove away,
and, uh, you did what?

1040
01:28:32,202 --> 01:28:35,296
I went to bed.

1041
01:28:35,372 --> 01:28:40,036
Freddie's a big man, but I'm in trouble
after a couple of drinks.

1042
01:28:40,110 --> 01:28:43,477
I've been suffering all--

1043
01:28:43,547 --> 01:28:45,606
Who found him?

1044
01:28:45,682 --> 01:28:48,276
You understand, I must ask you...

1045
01:28:48,352 --> 01:28:50,912
to stay in Rome, Signor Greenleaf.

1046
01:28:50,988 --> 01:28:54,321
Yes, if it's gonna help, certainly.

1047
01:28:54,391 --> 01:28:58,191
<i>So, the doctor,
he has to make the, um--</i>

1048
01:29:01,665 --> 01:29:04,896
- Postmortem.
- Yeah, exactly.

1049
01:29:04,968 --> 01:29:07,630
But, you know, his first conclusion...

1050
01:29:07,704 --> 01:29:12,767
was that Signor Miles was killed
not later than 7:00 yesterday evening.

1051
01:29:12,843 --> 01:29:16,244
Well, he certainly wasn't dead
when he drove away in his car.

1052
01:29:18,348 --> 01:29:20,282
No.

1053
01:29:45,609 --> 01:29:48,100
It's okay.

1054
01:29:48,178 --> 01:29:50,578
- Okay?
- <i>Si, si.</i>

1055
01:30:00,958 --> 01:30:04,553
- Did he kill Freddie?
- Marge. When did you get here?

1056
01:30:04,628 --> 01:30:07,256
Tell me the truth.
Did he kill Freddie?

1057
01:30:07,331 --> 01:30:10,858
I'd swear he didn't.
Of course he didn't.

1058
01:30:10,934 --> 01:30:15,166
I tried again.
Waiting here, watching for him.

1059
01:30:15,239 --> 01:30:18,834
Instead, it's you.
Whenever I look for Dickie, I find you.

1060
01:30:20,744 --> 01:30:23,736
What happened to your face?

1061
01:30:23,814 --> 01:30:25,748
Dickie-- Dickie did it.

1062
01:30:25,816 --> 01:30:28,046
- Dickie?
- My face. There was an argument.

1063
01:30:28,118 --> 01:30:30,814
I-- I said some things
I shouldn't have said and I--

1064
01:30:30,888 --> 01:30:34,517
About you. About the appalling way
he's treating you, all of us.

1065
01:30:34,591 --> 01:30:36,889
<i>And the next thing I know,
he's launched himself at me.</i>

1066
01:30:36,960 --> 01:30:39,087
- Are you getting on?
- What?

1067
01:30:39,163 --> 01:30:41,324
Get on. I'll take you to him.

1068
01:31:25,809 --> 01:31:28,039
- Where does he live?
- We passed it a few blocks back.

1069
01:31:28,111 --> 01:31:30,545
It's where the police were.
The Palazzo Gioia.

1070
01:31:32,549 --> 01:31:35,518
Look, they don't even know I'm in Rome,
and I'm not gonna incriminate Dickie.

1071
01:31:35,586 --> 01:31:37,611
Well, perhaps I shouldn't go either.

1072
01:31:37,688 --> 01:31:41,317
No. Well, go if you want to, but just
don't talk to the police about my face.

1073
01:31:41,391 --> 01:31:44,758
If they know he hit me and his temper,
then he could've hit Freddie.

1074
01:31:44,828 --> 01:31:46,819
I'll catch up with you later.

1075
01:32:05,083 --> 01:32:08,052
Signor Greenleaf!

1076
01:32:08,119 --> 01:32:10,713
It's Signor Greenleaf!
<i>Presto, presto!</i>

1077
01:32:16,194 --> 01:32:18,389
Open the door!

1078
01:32:18,463 --> 01:32:20,863
Open up!

1079
01:32:20,932 --> 01:32:23,196
I live here!

1080
01:32:24,369 --> 01:32:26,303
Mr. Greenleaf!

1081
01:32:27,672 --> 01:32:29,867
Can we go up? Do you mind?

1082
01:32:29,941 --> 01:32:32,535
Of course.
What happened to your face?

1083
01:32:32,610 --> 01:32:36,307
My scooter. I fell off
getting chased by photographers.

1084
01:32:36,381 --> 01:32:40,408
The telephone, the press, I've been--
I'm feeling hounded.

1085
01:32:40,485 --> 01:32:42,612
Do you think you could
not give out my address?

1086
01:32:42,687 --> 01:32:47,317
Never. We've had many requests,
and we say no, even to your fianc√©e.

1087
01:32:47,392 --> 01:32:49,326
I really don't want to see anybody.

1088
01:32:49,394 --> 01:32:52,158
- <i>Even your fianc√©e?</i>
- Even her.

1089
01:32:55,266 --> 01:32:58,463
- <i>What about Thomas Ripley?</i>
- What about Tom Ripley?

1090
01:33:00,471 --> 01:33:02,462
You and Signor Ripley went to San Remo.
Is that right?

1091
01:33:02,540 --> 01:33:05,668
Yes, we-- We went to San Remo.
That was months ago.

1092
01:33:05,743 --> 01:33:07,904
November, I thought. Was it?

1093
01:33:07,979 --> 01:33:11,540
- Did you speak to Tom?
- November 7 is my information.

1094
01:33:11,616 --> 01:33:14,346
<i>I don't remember the exact date.</i>

1095
01:33:14,419 --> 01:33:18,856
- When did you last see Signor Ripley?
- A few days ago.

1096
01:33:18,923 --> 01:33:22,518
- <i>Does he stay with you here?</i>
- No.

1097
01:33:22,593 --> 01:33:24,959
<i>No.</i>

1098
01:33:26,331 --> 01:33:29,300
Here is a pattern.
Two days ago,

1099
01:33:29,367 --> 01:33:32,359
Freddie Miles is dead, hmm?

1100
01:33:33,604 --> 01:33:36,072
<i>He leaves your apartment,</i>

1101
01:33:37,141 --> 01:33:39,905
and he's murdered.

1102
01:33:39,977 --> 01:33:45,108
Yesterday, a little boat
is found in San Remo full of rocks.

1103
01:33:45,183 --> 01:33:50,052
<i>And the owner tells the police
it was stolen on November 7.</i>

1104
01:33:50,121 --> 01:33:52,612
<i>We look at hotel records...</i>

1105
01:33:52,690 --> 01:33:55,488
and we see...

1106
01:33:55,560 --> 01:33:58,757
Dickie Greenleaf is staying in San Remo.

1107
01:33:58,830 --> 01:34:02,596
And then our boatman remembers
two Americans taking a boat.

1108
01:34:02,667 --> 01:34:05,465
That is not a pattern.
That's a coincidence.

1109
01:34:05,536 --> 01:34:07,504
There must be 50 hotels in San Remo.

1110
01:34:07,572 --> 01:34:10,405
There were probably a hundred people
renting a boat that day.

1111
01:34:10,475 --> 01:34:12,966
Thirty-one people.

1112
01:34:13,044 --> 01:34:15,069
Thirty-one people.

1113
01:34:16,180 --> 01:34:18,114
Thirty-one, yeah.

1114
01:34:20,351 --> 01:34:22,945
- <i>Marge Sherwood.</i>
- That is Miss Sherwood now.

1115
01:34:31,696 --> 01:34:33,721
Let her in.

1116
01:34:33,798 --> 01:34:36,460
Let her in.
What's the difference? Let her in.

1117
01:34:38,903 --> 01:34:42,339
No! Actually-- Actually, no.

1118
01:34:42,407 --> 01:34:45,308
I would-- I would really appreciate it...

1119
01:34:45,376 --> 01:34:48,243
<i>if you would ask Miss Sherwood
to come back later.</i>

1120
01:34:52,784 --> 01:34:55,651
Thank you.

1121
01:34:55,720 --> 01:34:59,315
May I ask you--

1122
01:34:59,390 --> 01:35:02,951
Why would you speak to your friend
and not your fianc√©e?

1123
01:35:03,027 --> 01:35:06,360
Well, I-- I think I just said.

1124
01:35:06,431 --> 01:35:09,764
<i>Um, Mr. Ripley was handling
some business for me.</i>

1125
01:35:09,834 --> 01:35:12,462
<i>Nor does Mr. Ripley
want to marry me...</i>

1126
01:35:12,537 --> 01:35:16,564
and ask me every single day
if I'll marry him and when.

1127
01:35:17,742 --> 01:35:19,733
Do you keep a photograph of Signor Ripley?

1128
01:35:19,811 --> 01:35:23,679
I'm not in the habit of carrying
around photographs of my male friends.

1129
01:35:25,316 --> 01:35:27,250
Now I think I've upset you.

1130
01:35:27,318 --> 01:35:30,446
Sorry. My English, perhaps, is coarse.

1131
01:35:30,521 --> 01:35:32,989
It is a little coarse, yes.

1132
01:35:36,494 --> 01:35:38,428
I'm sorry.

1133
01:35:38,496 --> 01:35:43,490
<i>But you-- No one has seen
Signor Ripley since San Remo.</i>

1134
01:35:43,568 --> 01:35:45,502
- I have.
- You have, yes.

1135
01:35:45,570 --> 01:35:48,300
And so has Miss Sherwood.
Ask her. And, um,

1136
01:35:48,372 --> 01:35:53,503
if I can remember the name
of the hotel he was staying at--

1137
01:35:53,578 --> 01:35:56,604
Um, the Goldoni.
Tom was staying at the Goldoni.

1138
01:35:56,681 --> 01:36:00,082
Goldoni. The Goldoni.
Good, good, but--

1139
01:36:00,151 --> 01:36:02,711
Yes, you are right.

1140
01:36:02,787 --> 01:36:05,051
You are right. A coincidence.

1141
01:36:07,124 --> 01:36:10,719
I look forward to our next meeting.

1142
01:36:10,795 --> 01:36:12,786
Hmm? When I will be more careful
with my English.

1143
01:36:12,864 --> 01:36:17,130
<i>Ah. I have a witness
who thinks they saw two men...</i>

1144
01:36:17,201 --> 01:36:19,135
<i>getting into Mr. Miles' car.</i>

1145
01:36:19,203 --> 01:36:23,105
<i>And she wants to identify you
in a</i> confronto.

1146
01:36:23,174 --> 01:36:25,665
Lineup. Tomorrow, then?

1147
01:36:27,178 --> 01:36:29,112
Uh, tomorrow.

1148
01:36:36,721 --> 01:36:38,655
- Buon giorno, <i>Miss Sherwood.</i>
- Buon giorno.

1149
01:36:38,723 --> 01:36:42,887
<i>He's in, but I really don't think
he wants to meet anybody.</i>

1150
01:37:00,278 --> 01:37:02,212
Dick?

1151
01:37:05,683 --> 01:37:07,844
Dickie?

1152
01:37:09,387 --> 01:37:11,321
<i>I know you can hear me.</i>

1153
01:37:20,164 --> 01:37:23,463
I was gonna say that I would count to three,
and if you didn't open the door--

1154
01:37:23,534 --> 01:37:27,800
But I won't count anymore.

1155
01:37:27,872 --> 01:37:29,863
On you.

1156
01:37:31,909 --> 01:37:35,401
I won't count on you anymore.

1157
01:37:38,883 --> 01:37:43,786
Whatever it is you've done
or haven't done,

1158
01:37:43,854 --> 01:37:46,345
you've broken my heart.

1159
01:37:48,593 --> 01:37:51,027
<i>That's one thing
I know you're guilty of.</i>

1160
01:37:58,603 --> 01:38:01,037
And I don't know why.

1161
01:38:03,541 --> 01:38:06,942
I don't know why.
I just don't know why.

1162
01:38:16,787 --> 01:38:19,017
<i>My dear Tom,</i>

1163
01:38:19,090 --> 01:38:22,617
<i>I'm getting out of this.</i>

1164
01:38:22,693 --> 01:38:26,220
<i>Freddie's death. Silvana.</i>

1165
01:38:26,297 --> 01:38:30,495
<i>I've thought about going to the police,
but I can't do it.</i>

1166
01:38:30,568 --> 01:38:32,934
<i>I can't face it.</i>

1167
01:38:33,004 --> 01:38:34,763
<i>I can't face anything anymore.</i>

1168
01:38:35,838 --> 01:38:38,602
<i>I wish I could give you
the life I took for granted.</i>

1169
01:38:41,678 --> 01:38:44,238
<i>You've always understood
what's at the heart of me, Tom.</i>

1170
01:38:44,313 --> 01:38:47,680
<i>Marge never could.</i>

1171
01:38:47,750 --> 01:38:51,151
<i>I suppose that's why
I'm writing this to you,</i>

1172
01:38:51,220 --> 01:38:53,848
<i>the brother I never had.</i>

1173
01:38:53,923 --> 01:38:56,653
<i>The only true friend I ever had.</i>

1174
01:39:02,331 --> 01:39:04,265
<i>In all kinds of ways,</i>

1175
01:39:04,333 --> 01:39:08,633
<i>you're much more
like the son my father wanted.</i>

1176
01:39:08,705 --> 01:39:11,936
<i>I realize you can change the people,</i>

1177
01:39:12,008 --> 01:39:14,499
<i>change the scenery,</i>

1178
01:39:14,577 --> 01:39:16,772
<i>but you can't change
your own rotten self.</i>

1179
01:39:19,582 --> 01:39:22,312
<i>Now I can't think what to do
or where to go.</i>

1180
01:39:24,420 --> 01:39:28,982
<i>I'm haunted by everything I've done
and can't undo.</i>

1181
01:39:30,593 --> 01:39:32,527
<i>I'm sorry.</i>

1182
01:39:34,630 --> 01:39:37,997
<i>I've made a mess of being
Dickie Greenleaf, haven't I?</i>

1183
01:40:42,365 --> 01:40:45,357
<i>Tom!</i>

1184
01:40:47,537 --> 01:40:50,802
I'll see you over there!

1185
01:40:59,215 --> 01:41:01,513
I'm so sorry to put you
through this, Peter.

1186
01:41:01,584 --> 01:41:05,179
I just can't face going to the police by myself
when my Italian's so rotten.

1187
01:41:05,254 --> 01:41:07,245
Don't be so daft. It's fine.

1188
01:41:07,323 --> 01:41:09,985
I'm delighted you finally
made it to Venice.

1189
01:41:10,059 --> 01:41:12,687
I'm delighted, contrary to rumor,
that you're still in one piece.

1190
01:41:12,762 --> 01:41:14,753
- What rumor?
- Oh, you know.

1191
01:41:14,831 --> 01:41:18,267
That Dickie murdered you
and is traveling under your passport.

1192
01:41:18,334 --> 01:41:20,427
I know. It's ridiculous.

1193
01:41:35,284 --> 01:41:37,218
Welcome to Venice.

1194
01:41:37,286 --> 01:41:40,312
God, this place reeks, doesn't it?
Can you smell it?

1195
01:41:40,389 --> 01:41:44,257
Anyway, I've got to the bottom
of the delay, finally.

1196
01:41:44,327 --> 01:41:47,262
We're waiting for someone from Rome.

1197
01:41:47,330 --> 01:41:49,662
What do you mean?
They've sent for someone from Rome?

1198
01:41:49,732 --> 01:41:52,860
- Well, yes. That's good, isn't it?
- <i>No, I thought...</i>

1199
01:41:52,935 --> 01:41:56,302
that didn't happen in Italy,
that each region is separate.

1200
01:41:56,372 --> 01:41:58,806
I was sure that--
I've read that--

1201
01:41:58,875 --> 01:42:01,742
You've read the papers.
You know what a big deal it's been.

1202
01:42:01,811 --> 01:42:04,871
- <i>American tourist murdered.</i>
- Actually, can we not do this now?

1203
01:42:04,947 --> 01:42:09,008
The stench really is--

1204
01:42:26,302 --> 01:42:30,932
He's taken over the case, 'cause
they're annoyed that the previous chap...

1205
01:42:31,007 --> 01:42:33,874
<i>let Dickie disappear
when he was, um,</i>

1206
01:42:33,943 --> 01:42:35,934
<i>the only suspect in Freddie's murder.</i>

1207
01:42:38,981 --> 01:42:42,246
In Rome, about three weeks ago.

1208
01:42:42,318 --> 01:42:44,252
I knew that one.

1209
01:42:44,320 --> 01:42:48,381
Um--

1210
01:42:51,494 --> 01:42:56,329
Are you a homosexual?
Interesting non sequitur.

1211
01:42:56,399 --> 01:42:58,424
No.

1212
01:42:58,501 --> 01:43:01,732
- No.
- Oh.

1213
01:43:01,804 --> 01:43:06,707
By the way, um, officially
there are no Italian homosexuals.

1214
01:43:06,776 --> 01:43:09,301
Makes Michelangelo and Leonardo
very inconvenient.

1215
01:43:09,378 --> 01:43:11,073
Eh?

1216
01:43:11,147 --> 01:43:14,344
Tell him... I have a fianc√©e.

1217
01:43:14,417 --> 01:43:16,783
And Dickie has a fianc√©e.

1218
01:43:16,852 --> 01:43:20,481
And that Freddie Miles
probably had a string of them.

1219
01:43:32,134 --> 01:43:36,036
<i>Mamma mia.</i>

1220
01:43:39,608 --> 01:43:41,838
- What did he say?
- He says "so many fianc√©es."

1221
01:43:47,016 --> 01:43:49,985
<i>He's asking...
if you killed Freddie Miles...</i>

1222
01:43:50,052 --> 01:43:51,986
<i>and then killed Dickie Greenleaf.</i>

1223
01:43:52,054 --> 01:43:56,013
No! No, I did not kill Freddie Miles
and then kill Dickie Greenleaf.

1224
01:43:56,092 --> 01:43:59,289
<i>Is he accusing me?
Ask him if he's accusing me.</i>

1225
01:43:59,362 --> 01:44:02,126
The way it works here,
it's better to be less volatile.

1226
01:44:02,198 --> 01:44:04,359
<i>But it's absurd!</i>

1227
01:44:19,882 --> 01:44:24,342
They found this
in Dickie's place in Rome.

1228
01:44:24,420 --> 01:44:26,980
- You opened this?
- Of course.

1229
01:44:43,305 --> 01:44:46,138
It's a suicide note.

1230
01:44:49,945 --> 01:44:53,813
You asked me all these questions
and you already read this suicide note?

1231
01:45:12,168 --> 01:45:14,261
I don't believe that letter.
Do you?

1232
01:45:14,336 --> 01:45:17,863
Dickie's letter.
Do you believe it?

1233
01:45:17,940 --> 01:45:20,374
I don't know what to believe.

1234
01:45:20,443 --> 01:45:25,148
Can you imagine, though, if he did kill Freddie,
what that must be like?

1235
01:45:25,281 --> 01:45:29,115
Just to wake up every morning.
I mean, how can you?

1236
01:45:29,185 --> 01:45:32,677
Just wake up and be a person?
Drink your coffee.

1237
01:45:32,755 --> 01:45:37,158
Well, whatever you do,
however terrible, however hurtful,

1238
01:45:37,226 --> 01:45:40,525
it all makes sense, doesn't it,
in your head.

1239
01:45:40,596 --> 01:45:43,360
You never meet anybody
who thinks they're a bad person.

1240
01:45:43,432 --> 01:45:47,459
No, I know, but you're still tormented.
You must be. You've killed someone.

1241
01:45:47,537 --> 01:45:50,665
Don't you just take the past
and put it in a room in the basement,

1242
01:45:50,740 --> 01:45:52,731
and lock the door
and never go in there?

1243
01:45:52,808 --> 01:45:56,175
- That's what I do.
- God, yes.

1244
01:45:56,245 --> 01:46:00,875
But, of course, in my case,
it's probably a whole building.

1245
01:46:00,950 --> 01:46:03,976
And then you meet someone special,

1246
01:46:04,053 --> 01:46:08,114
and all you want to do
is toss them the key.

1247
01:46:09,458 --> 01:46:12,018
Say "Open up. Step inside."

1248
01:46:14,730 --> 01:46:16,960
But you can't...

1249
01:46:17,033 --> 01:46:19,797
because it's dark...

1250
01:46:19,869 --> 01:46:22,736
and there are demons.

1251
01:46:23,806 --> 01:46:26,240
And if anybody saw how ugly it is--

1252
01:46:30,947 --> 01:46:33,006
Now that's the music talking.

1253
01:46:35,284 --> 01:46:38,617
It's harder to be bleak if you're playing
"Knees Up, Mother Brown."

1254
01:46:44,327 --> 01:46:47,296
I keep wanting to do that.

1255
01:46:47,363 --> 01:46:51,231
Fling... the door open.

1256
01:46:53,603 --> 01:46:57,369
Just let the light in,
clean everything out.

1257
01:46:59,675 --> 01:47:03,668
If I could take a giant eraser
and rub out everything,

1258
01:47:03,746 --> 01:47:06,681
starting with myself--

1259
01:47:09,252 --> 01:47:12,483
<i>The thing is, Peter, if--</i>

1260
01:47:14,991 --> 01:47:18,654
- <i>Hmm?</i>
- If--

1261
01:47:20,496 --> 01:47:22,430
If--

1262
01:47:29,505 --> 01:47:31,837
No key, huh?

1263
01:48:16,252 --> 01:48:18,243
- Marge.
- Peter.

1264
01:48:20,690 --> 01:48:22,658
- So good to see you.
- Hello, Marge.

1265
01:48:22,725 --> 01:48:24,920
Tom.

1266
01:48:24,994 --> 01:48:29,055
- I see you found Peter.
- I think we sort of found each other.

1267
01:48:29,131 --> 01:48:32,828
- Where's Dickie's father?
- He's not coming till the morning.

1268
01:48:32,902 --> 01:48:36,463
Evidently his stomach. I don't think
the food here is agreeing with him.

1269
01:48:36,539 --> 01:48:38,473
Oh, I was looking forward
to seeing him.

1270
01:48:38,541 --> 01:48:41,271
Dickie hasn't killed himself.
I'm sure of that.

1271
01:48:41,344 --> 01:48:43,904
There's a private detective
on the case now.

1272
01:48:43,979 --> 01:48:46,470
A Mr. MacCarron Dickie's father's employed.

1273
01:48:46,549 --> 01:48:49,916
- That's a terrific idea.
- He's American.

1274
01:48:49,985 --> 01:48:53,318
He's already discovered that Dickie
cashed checks for $1,000...

1275
01:48:53,389 --> 01:48:55,584
the day before he disappeared.

1276
01:48:55,658 --> 01:48:57,592
Signora.

1277
01:48:57,660 --> 01:49:01,096
Is that what you do
before you jump into the Tiber?

1278
01:49:01,163 --> 01:49:03,757
<i>I don't think so.</i>

1279
01:49:07,570 --> 01:49:09,800
- Is this you?
- No, it's Tom's.

1280
01:49:09,872 --> 01:49:11,806
Splendid, eh?

1281
01:49:11,874 --> 01:49:15,207
Golly. Who's paying for this?

1282
01:49:15,277 --> 01:49:17,245
Peter found it for me.

1283
01:49:17,313 --> 01:49:22,216
I can afford it because it's damp and...
falling down.

1284
01:49:22,284 --> 01:49:25,447
- Tom's transformed it.
- This is spectacular.

1285
01:49:25,521 --> 01:49:27,785
That's why Tom wanted you to stay.

1286
01:49:27,857 --> 01:49:30,451
<i>It's better than trying
to squeeze into my room.</i>

1287
01:49:30,526 --> 01:49:32,619
<i>And I know how you hate hotels.</i>

1288
01:49:32,695 --> 01:49:34,686
A hotel would have been fine.

1289
01:49:38,134 --> 01:49:42,696
We'll have to tell Mr. Greenleaf
how far his dollar stretched.

1290
01:49:46,075 --> 01:49:49,101
What's funny?

1291
01:49:49,178 --> 01:49:52,705
I was just thinking about
when Tom first came to Mongibello.

1292
01:49:54,750 --> 01:49:58,208
- And look at you now.
- Look at me what?

1293
01:49:59,488 --> 01:50:01,456
To the manor born.

1294
01:50:15,604 --> 01:50:17,799
<i>Mr. Greenleaf?</i>

1295
01:50:21,710 --> 01:50:23,644
Mr. Greenleaf?

1296
01:50:23,712 --> 01:50:27,409
Tom. How are you?
You look well.

1297
01:50:27,483 --> 01:50:30,316
- Thank you, sir. I am well.
- Far cry from New York.

1298
01:50:30,386 --> 01:50:32,877
- <i>Yes, it is.</i>
- Marge.

1299
01:50:32,955 --> 01:50:36,015
Good morning. Unusual weather.

1300
01:50:36,091 --> 01:50:38,958
- Very.
- And you, sir. Any better?

1301
01:50:39,028 --> 01:50:42,122
Pretty good.
Sticking with hot water.

1302
01:50:42,198 --> 01:50:44,530
- Where's Mr. MacCarron?
- San Remo.

1303
01:50:44,600 --> 01:50:47,330
<i>The police are amateurs.</i>

1304
01:50:47,403 --> 01:50:51,931
<i>Well, my boy, it's come
to a pretty pass, hasn't it?</i>

1305
01:50:52,007 --> 01:50:55,204
What is the detective
hoping to find in San Remo?

1306
01:50:55,277 --> 01:51:00,112
<i>He's being thorough.
I'm learning about my son, Tom.</i>

1307
01:51:00,182 --> 01:51:03,618
Now he's missing,
I'm learning a great deal about him,

1308
01:51:03,686 --> 01:51:06,780
and I hope that you can fill in
some more blanks for me.

1309
01:51:06,856 --> 01:51:09,916
Marge has been good enough
to do that about Mongibello.

1310
01:51:09,992 --> 01:51:13,792
I'll try my best, sir. Obviously,
I'll do anything to help Dickie.

1311
01:51:13,863 --> 01:51:16,354
<i>Good. This theory,</i>

1312
01:51:16,432 --> 01:51:18,559
<i>the letter he left for you.</i>

1313
01:51:18,634 --> 01:51:21,899
<i>The police think that's
a clear indication...</i>

1314
01:51:21,971 --> 01:51:25,702
he was planning on doing something,
uh, to himself.

1315
01:51:25,774 --> 01:51:28,572
I just don't believe that.

1316
01:51:28,644 --> 01:51:31,169
You don't want to, dear.

1317
01:51:34,383 --> 01:51:36,408
I'd like to talk to Tom alone.

1318
01:51:36,485 --> 01:51:39,283
<i>Perhaps this afternoon.
Would you mind?</i>

1319
01:51:41,724 --> 01:51:45,751
Marge, what a man may say
to his sweetheart...

1320
01:51:45,828 --> 01:51:47,989
and what he'll admit
to another fellow--

1321
01:51:51,300 --> 01:51:53,996
Such as?

1322
01:51:57,706 --> 01:52:00,971
What a waste of lives and opportunities.

1323
01:52:01,043 --> 01:52:04,069
I'd pay that fellow a hundred dollars
right now to shut up!

1324
01:52:12,388 --> 01:52:15,755
No, Marge doesn't know
the half of it.

1325
01:52:15,824 --> 01:52:19,089
And his passport photo.

1326
01:52:19,161 --> 01:52:22,065
Did you hear?
To scratch out his own face like that?

1327
01:52:22,198 --> 01:52:24,325
Can you imagine?

1328
01:52:24,400 --> 01:52:27,665
Frame of mind you'd have to be in?

1329
01:52:27,737 --> 01:52:31,036
"I've thought about going to the police,
but I can't face it.

1330
01:52:31,107 --> 01:52:34,634
I can't face anything anymore."

1331
01:52:34,710 --> 01:52:38,043
I feel guilty.
I feel like I pushed him away.

1332
01:52:38,114 --> 01:52:40,173
I feel like I spoke
and he heard you.

1333
01:52:40,249 --> 01:52:43,047
Well,

1334
01:52:43,119 --> 01:52:45,713
if we all pushed him away,
what about him pushing us away?

1335
01:52:45,788 --> 01:52:48,382
You've been a great friend to my son.

1336
01:52:48,458 --> 01:52:51,586
Everything is someone else's fault.

1337
01:52:51,661 --> 01:52:54,129
<i>We all want to sow wild oats,</i>

1338
01:52:54,197 --> 01:52:57,530
but somebody's got to--
got to--

1339
01:52:57,600 --> 01:53:00,398
What is the word?

1340
01:53:00,470 --> 01:53:03,667
You know, the moment
someone confronts him,

1341
01:53:05,041 --> 01:53:07,566
he lashes out.

1342
01:53:07,643 --> 01:53:10,203
He always has.

1343
01:53:10,279 --> 01:53:14,147
You know, people always say
that you can't choose your parents,

1344
01:53:18,888 --> 01:53:21,379
but you can't choose your children.

1345
01:53:22,758 --> 01:53:26,319
<i>Dickie.</i>

1346
01:53:26,395 --> 01:53:29,990
<i>You can be a leech.
You can be quite boring.</i>

1347
01:53:30,066 --> 01:53:32,000
- <i>Stop it!</i>
- <i>It's boring.</i>

1348
01:53:36,105 --> 01:53:38,437
<i>Stop, stop, stop!</i>

1349
01:53:39,942 --> 01:53:41,842
- <i>Stop, stop, stop!</i>
- <i>Tommy, Tommy.</i>

1350
01:53:41,911 --> 01:53:43,845
<i>Like a little girl.</i>

1351
01:53:43,913 --> 01:53:47,007
<i>Like a little girl.</i>

1352
01:53:50,653 --> 01:53:52,621
Coming.

1353
01:53:52,688 --> 01:53:55,054
- Sorry. I was asleep.
- Finally.

1354
01:53:55,124 --> 01:53:57,251
- I must have fallen asleep.
- Did Dickie's dad go?

1355
01:53:57,326 --> 01:53:59,260
You look ghastly, Tom.
Did you have a nightmare?

1356
01:53:59,328 --> 01:54:02,525
- He's having an early night.
- <i>Oh, poor man.</i>

1357
01:54:02,598 --> 01:54:05,089
<i>You know, we were banging
on that door forever.</i>

1358
01:54:08,671 --> 01:54:10,605
<i>Uh-oh.</i>

1359
01:54:10,673 --> 01:54:14,268
- I think I've broken a strap.
- Not guilty.

1360
01:54:14,343 --> 01:54:17,312
I'll fix some drinks.

1361
01:54:17,380 --> 01:54:20,008
Ah! You walk in Venice.

1362
01:54:21,551 --> 01:54:23,485
Are you okay?

1363
01:54:24,954 --> 01:54:26,819
I'm fine.

1364
01:54:26,889 --> 01:54:31,053
- Did you want me to stick around?
- No, it's okay.

1365
01:54:33,095 --> 01:54:35,290
I could come back.

1366
01:54:50,613 --> 01:54:52,740
Your key.

1367
01:54:56,452 --> 01:54:59,148
<i>Tom?</i>

1368
01:54:59,222 --> 01:55:02,714
Marge, I'm in the bath.
I won't be long.

1369
01:55:02,792 --> 01:55:05,022
<i>Tom, I have to speak to you.
It's urgent.</i>

1370
01:55:08,764 --> 01:55:10,698
Coming.

1371
01:55:22,211 --> 01:55:25,510
- I found Dickie's rings.
- What?

1372
01:55:25,581 --> 01:55:27,572
You have Dickie's rings.

1373
01:55:32,355 --> 01:55:34,289
I can explain.

1374
01:55:34,357 --> 01:55:37,053
<i>Dickie promised me
he would never take off this ring.</i>

1375
01:55:37,126 --> 01:55:40,186
Let me put some clothes on
and we'll talk about this.

1376
01:55:40,263 --> 01:55:42,697
- I have to tell Mr. Greenleaf.
- Marge, you're being hysterical.

1377
01:55:42,765 --> 01:55:46,223
He promised me, "I swear, I will never
take off this ring until we get--"

1378
01:55:46,302 --> 01:55:48,236
Shut up!

1379
01:55:50,439 --> 01:55:53,897
I'm wet, Marge.
I've lost my towel.

1380
01:55:53,976 --> 01:55:56,968
<i>And I'd really like to put
some clothes on.</i>

1381
01:55:57,046 --> 01:55:59,071
Go and pour us both a drink.

1382
01:56:02,485 --> 01:56:04,419
Pour us a drink.

1383
01:56:37,787 --> 01:56:40,119
Marge?

1384
01:56:40,189 --> 01:56:42,453
Where are you going?

1385
01:56:42,525 --> 01:56:45,983
I wasn't snooping. I just--

1386
01:56:46,062 --> 01:56:48,997
I was looking for a needle
and thread to mend my bra.

1387
01:56:51,000 --> 01:56:54,595
That scent you're wearing.

1388
01:56:54,670 --> 01:56:57,901
I bought that for you.

1389
01:56:57,973 --> 01:57:00,533
The thing about Dickie--

1390
01:57:00,609 --> 01:57:02,543
<i>So many things.</i>

1391
01:57:04,480 --> 01:57:08,041
That day when he was late
coming back from Rome,

1392
01:57:08,117 --> 01:57:10,051
I tried to tell you this.

1393
01:57:10,119 --> 01:57:13,611
He was with another girl.
I'm not talking about Meredith, either.

1394
01:57:13,689 --> 01:57:16,920
Another girl that we met in a bar.

1395
01:57:16,992 --> 01:57:20,052
<i>He couldn't be faithful
for five minutes.</i>

1396
01:57:20,129 --> 01:57:22,154
<i>So when he makes a promise,</i>

1397
01:57:22,231 --> 01:57:24,290
it doesn't mean what it means
when you make a promise...

1398
01:57:24,367 --> 01:57:26,927
or I make a promise.

1399
01:57:27,002 --> 01:57:30,995
He has so many realities, Dickie,
and he believes them all.

1400
01:57:31,073 --> 01:57:34,270
He lies. He lies.

1401
01:57:34,343 --> 01:57:38,746
And that's his-- Half the time
he doesn't even realize he's doing it.

1402
01:57:38,814 --> 01:57:42,113
And today,

1403
01:57:42,184 --> 01:57:45,984
I really started wondering
whether he may have killed Freddie.

1404
01:57:46,055 --> 01:57:49,650
<i>He would get so crazy
if anybody would contradict him.</i>

1405
01:57:49,725 --> 01:57:52,421
Well, you know that.
You know that.

1406
01:57:52,495 --> 01:57:55,123
<i>You know that.</i>

1407
01:57:55,197 --> 01:57:57,461
<i>And that's the irony, Marge.</i>

1408
01:57:57,533 --> 01:57:59,467
I loved you.

1409
01:57:59,535 --> 01:58:01,469
You may as well know, Marge.
I loved you.

1410
01:58:01,537 --> 01:58:04,267
<i>I don't know, maybe it's grotesque of me
to say this now,</i>

1411
01:58:04,340 --> 01:58:07,173
<i>so just... write it on a
piece of paper or something...</i>

1412
01:58:07,243 --> 01:58:09,711
<i>and put it in your purse
for a rainy day.</i>

1413
01:58:09,779 --> 01:58:14,011
"Tom loves me. Tom loves me."

1414
01:58:14,083 --> 01:58:16,449
- Why do you have Dickie's rings?
- I told you.

1415
01:58:16,519 --> 01:58:19,613
- He gave them to me.
- Why? When?

1416
01:58:19,688 --> 01:58:22,714
<i>I feel as if you haven't been listening
to anything I've been saying to you.</i>

1417
01:58:22,792 --> 01:58:26,057
I don't believe you.
I don't believe you.

1418
01:58:26,128 --> 01:58:28,460
- It's all true.
- I don't believe...

1419
01:58:28,531 --> 01:58:32,934
a single word you've said.

1420
01:58:33,002 --> 01:58:35,732
You're shivering, Marge.
Look at you.

1421
01:58:35,805 --> 01:58:39,605
<i>Marge, can I hold you?</i>

1422
01:58:39,675 --> 01:58:41,643
Will you let me hold you?

1423
01:58:41,710 --> 01:58:43,812
<i>Marge?</i>

1424
01:58:43,945 --> 01:58:47,005
- Peter! Thank God you're here.
- <i>What's going on?</i>

1425
01:58:47,081 --> 01:58:50,414
<i>Get me out of here.
Get me out of here. Please!</i>

1426
01:58:50,485 --> 01:58:55,320
<i>Tom, are you okay?</i>

1427
01:58:55,390 --> 01:58:58,518
You try. You try talking to her.

1428
01:58:59,594 --> 01:59:01,687
- <i>Tom?</i>
- I give up.

1429
01:59:01,763 --> 01:59:04,357
<i>Tell me what's going on. Tom!</i>

1430
01:59:04,432 --> 01:59:06,900
- <i>What did I ever do to her?</i>
- Listen--

1431
01:59:06,968 --> 01:59:10,096
<i>Have her tell you one thing
that I've ever done to her.</i>

1432
01:59:10,171 --> 01:59:12,867
You can't be angry with her.

1433
01:59:12,941 --> 01:59:15,876
She's confused,
and she needs someone to blame.

1434
01:59:15,944 --> 01:59:17,878
So she blames you.

1435
01:59:17,946 --> 01:59:20,506
I'll go back home and talk to her.

1436
01:59:20,582 --> 01:59:23,073
As for you,

1437
01:59:23,151 --> 01:59:25,779
either get a safety razor
or grow a beard.

1438
01:59:38,800 --> 01:59:41,963
- Is Mr. Greenleaf here?
- Mr. Ripley?

1439
01:59:42,036 --> 01:59:44,732
- Yes.
- I'm Alvin MacCarron.

1440
01:59:47,408 --> 01:59:50,104
<i>I don't know, I don't know.
I just know it.</i>

1441
01:59:50,178 --> 01:59:53,113
<i>Marge, there's female intuition
and then there are facts.</i>

1442
01:59:55,683 --> 01:59:57,617
- Tom.
- <i>Sir.</i>

1443
01:59:57,685 --> 02:00:00,415
Marge, you should have waited.
I didn't--

1444
02:00:00,488 --> 02:00:03,150
<i>Didn't Peter say I'd come by
and pick you up?</i>

1445
02:00:04,292 --> 02:00:06,886
Marge has been telling us
about the rings.

1446
02:00:06,961 --> 02:00:09,452
<i>Yes, I feel ridiculous
I didn't mention them yesterday.</i>

1447
02:00:09,530 --> 02:00:11,964
I clean forgot. Ridiculous.

1448
02:00:14,535 --> 02:00:18,835
Perhaps you didn't mention them because
there's only one conclusion to be drawn.

1449
02:00:20,909 --> 02:00:24,174
<i>I'm going to take Marge for a walk.
Tom, Mr. MacCarron needs to talk to you.</i>

1450
02:00:24,245 --> 02:00:26,475
There's no need. We could go to the bar.
There's no need.

1451
02:00:26,547 --> 02:00:28,742
No, no.

1452
02:00:28,816 --> 02:00:31,080
<i>I think you should stay here.</i>

1453
02:00:52,941 --> 02:00:55,432
I could probably see my room from here.

1454
02:00:55,510 --> 02:00:57,444
I can see my house.

1455
02:00:59,447 --> 02:01:03,577
When you see where you live from a distance,
it's like a dream, isn't it?

1456
02:01:03,651 --> 02:01:05,915
I don't care for B.S.

1457
02:01:05,987 --> 02:01:08,615
I don't care to hear it.
I don't care to speak it.

1458
02:01:10,858 --> 02:01:13,122
- Okay.
- Did you know that at Princeton...

1459
02:01:13,194 --> 02:01:15,526
Dickie Greenleaf half-killed a boy?

1460
02:01:16,597 --> 02:01:18,622
<i>At a party over some girl.</i>

1461
02:01:18,700 --> 02:01:22,568
<i>Kicked the kid several times in the head,
put him in the hospital.</i>

1462
02:01:22,637 --> 02:01:26,471
Boy had a wire fixed in his jaw,
lost some hearing.

1463
02:01:26,541 --> 02:01:29,840
<i>Why do you think Dickie's father
sent him to Europe in the first place?</i>

1464
02:01:32,547 --> 02:01:36,745
The Rome police didn't think
to ask Mr. Greenleaf.

1465
02:01:36,818 --> 02:01:39,810
Nor did they think to check
on whether a Thomas Ripley...

1466
02:01:39,887 --> 02:01:43,050
<i>had ever been a student
at Princeton University.</i>

1467
02:01:43,124 --> 02:01:47,754
Oh, I turned up a Tom Ripley...

1468
02:01:47,829 --> 02:01:51,925
who had been a piano tuner
in the music department.

1469
02:01:53,001 --> 02:01:55,094
You see, in America,

1470
02:01:55,169 --> 02:01:59,697
we are taught to check a fact
before it becomes a fact.

1471
02:01:59,774 --> 02:02:02,174
We're taught to nose around.

1472
02:02:02,243 --> 02:02:05,110
When a girl drowns herself,

1473
02:02:05,179 --> 02:02:07,579
find out if that girl is pregnant.

1474
02:02:07,648 --> 02:02:10,583
<i>Find out if Dickie
had an embarrassment there.</i>

1475
02:02:11,986 --> 02:02:15,353
Mr. Greenleaf appreciates your loyalty.
He really does.

1476
02:02:15,423 --> 02:02:18,483
Marge--
She has a hundred theories.

1477
02:02:18,559 --> 02:02:21,494
There are a few things
that she doesn't know.

1478
02:02:21,562 --> 02:02:23,553
We hope she never knows.

1479
02:02:23,631 --> 02:02:25,861
I hope she never knows.

1480
02:02:25,933 --> 02:02:28,424
Three different people...

1481
02:02:28,503 --> 02:02:32,064
saw Dickie get into Freddie's car.

1482
02:02:32,140 --> 02:02:35,439
One man, who will not testify...

1483
02:02:35,510 --> 02:02:38,445
because he was jumping
somebody else's wife at the time,

1484
02:02:38,513 --> 02:02:42,506
saw Dickie removing license plates
from a red sports car.

1485
02:02:42,583 --> 02:02:46,576
The police know about this man
because he happens to be a policeman.

1486
02:02:48,623 --> 02:02:52,081
I found these in the basement
of Dickie's apartment.

1487
02:02:52,160 --> 02:02:54,253
They belong to Freddie's car.

1488
02:02:54,328 --> 02:02:58,628
Mr. Greenleaf has asked me...

1489
02:02:58,699 --> 02:03:01,600
to lose these in the canal this evening.

1490
02:03:06,774 --> 02:03:09,641
Mr. Greenleaf feels that
there was a silent promise...

1491
02:03:09,710 --> 02:03:12,873
in Dickie's letter to you
which he intends to honor.

1492
02:03:12,947 --> 02:03:15,507
<i>He also intends to transfer
a good portion...</i>

1493
02:03:15,583 --> 02:03:20,316
of Dickie's income from his trust
into your name.

1494
02:03:20,388 --> 02:03:22,481
<i>He does not intend...</i>

1495
02:03:22,557 --> 02:03:26,015
<i>to give the Italians any information
about Dickie's past.</i>

1496
02:03:27,962 --> 02:03:31,796
He's rather hoping that...
you will feel the same.

1497
02:03:49,817 --> 02:03:51,751
- Thank you so much, Tom.
- Sir.

1498
02:03:51,819 --> 02:03:53,753
Good-bye.

1499
02:03:58,392 --> 02:04:02,692
Marge, I feel I never should have said
those things to you the other evening.

1500
02:04:02,763 --> 02:04:06,790
I was pretty flustered, and the rings--
And you looked so--

1501
02:04:06,868 --> 02:04:09,132
I don't know.

1502
02:04:09,203 --> 02:04:13,264
But I hope that note goes
in your purse to New York...

1503
02:04:13,341 --> 02:04:15,809
for a rainy day.

1504
02:04:17,378 --> 02:04:21,075
- What are you gonna do now, Tom?
- I don't know.

1505
02:04:21,149 --> 02:04:23,276
Peter has a concert in Athens next month,

1506
02:04:23,351 --> 02:04:25,945
so he asked me to come along 
and help out.

1507
02:04:28,523 --> 02:04:30,457
He says good-bye.

1508
02:04:30,525 --> 02:04:32,493
By the way,
he was in rehearsal so he couldn't--

1509
02:04:32,560 --> 02:04:36,758
Why do I think there's never been
a Ripley rainy day?

1510
02:04:36,831 --> 02:04:39,425
What?

1511
02:04:39,500 --> 02:04:43,231
I know it was you.
I know it was you.

1512
02:04:43,304 --> 02:04:46,137
I know it was you!
I know it was you!

1513
02:04:46,207 --> 02:04:49,870
- Marge, Marge. Please!
- I know you killed Dickie!

1514
02:04:49,944 --> 02:04:51,878
- Marge!
- I know! No!

1515
02:04:51,946 --> 02:04:55,438
I know it was you!

1516
02:04:55,516 --> 02:04:57,541
Marge. Marge, please.

1517
02:04:57,618 --> 02:05:00,280
It's not Tom. Really.

1518
02:05:08,863 --> 02:05:12,128
<i>We are called gondoleri</i>

1519
02:05:12,200 --> 02:05:16,159
<i>But that's a vagary
It's quite honorary</i>

1520
02:05:16,370 --> 02:05:21,708
<i>The trade that we ply</i>

1521
02:05:21,841 --> 02:05:24,571
Ask me what I want to change
about this moment.

1522
02:05:24,644 --> 02:05:27,112
I don't know. What do you want
to change about this moment?

1523
02:05:27,180 --> 02:05:28,875
Nothing.

1524
02:05:32,552 --> 02:05:35,350
I'm freezing. Coming down?

1525
02:05:35,421 --> 02:05:38,254
Later. I want to catch the sunset.

1526
02:05:38,324 --> 02:05:42,590
- You're mad.
- I am.

1527
02:05:52,505 --> 02:05:54,439
<i>Dickie?</i>

1528
02:05:57,643 --> 02:05:59,577
<i>Dickie?</i>

1529
02:06:02,982 --> 02:06:04,916
<i>Dickie!</i>

1530
02:06:15,995 --> 02:06:17,929
Oh, my God.

1531
02:06:19,899 --> 02:06:21,833
Hello, Meredith.

1532
02:06:24,971 --> 02:06:27,303
I was looking at you.

1533
02:06:27,373 --> 02:06:30,809
<i>Your clothes.
I wouldn't have known you.</i>

1534
02:06:30,877 --> 02:06:33,641
<i>Well, you spotted me,
so you get the reward.</i>

1535
02:06:35,314 --> 02:06:37,976
- What?
- Just kidding.

1536
02:06:38,050 --> 02:06:42,009
- Are you alone?
- Oh.

1537
02:06:42,088 --> 02:06:45,114
<i>Hardly. Couldn't be less alone.</i>

1538
02:06:45,191 --> 02:06:47,853
- Aunt Joan.
- And "co."

1539
02:06:50,997 --> 02:06:52,965
A lot of "co."

1540
02:06:54,100 --> 02:06:57,228
Oh, God.

1541
02:06:57,303 --> 02:07:00,397
<i>You know, seeing you again, I--</i>

1542
02:07:02,475 --> 02:07:05,740
I've thought about you...

1543
02:07:05,812 --> 02:07:07,746
so much.

1544
02:07:07,814 --> 02:07:09,748
And I've thought about you.

1545
02:07:11,818 --> 02:07:15,254
Yeah, well, when I've thought about you,
I was mostly hating you.

1546
02:07:21,861 --> 02:07:23,829
Where have you been hiding?

1547
02:07:23,896 --> 02:07:27,423
I haven't been hiding.

1548
02:07:27,500 --> 02:07:29,832
I've been in police custody.

1549
02:07:31,170 --> 02:07:34,105
They've been trying to flush out
Freddie's killer.

1550
02:07:34,173 --> 02:07:37,370
- You're kidding.
- They're giving me this vacation,

1551
02:07:37,443 --> 02:07:39,741
which is why the getup.

1552
02:07:39,812 --> 02:07:41,973
Which is why you haven't heard from me.

1553
02:07:42,048 --> 02:07:44,346
You know, the whole world
thinks you killed Freddie.

1554
02:07:44,417 --> 02:07:47,511
- Oh! It's terrible.
- I know.

1555
02:07:47,587 --> 02:07:50,283
Listen, I can't talk now. Um, later?

1556
02:07:54,260 --> 02:07:57,627
Later? Later?

1557
02:08:07,874 --> 02:08:09,808
So--

1558
02:08:15,081 --> 02:08:17,743
Are you traveling under "R"?

1559
02:08:17,817 --> 02:08:20,877
You know what? I am.

1560
02:08:23,956 --> 02:08:28,325
Dickie, are you with Peter Smith-Kingsley?
I bet you are.

1561
02:08:28,394 --> 02:08:31,022
My aunt thought she saw him.

1562
02:08:31,097 --> 02:08:33,224
Peter Smith-Kingsley?
No, I--

1563
02:08:33,299 --> 02:08:36,928
I haven't seen him in months.

1564
02:08:37,003 --> 02:08:38,937
No, I'm alone.

1565
02:08:58,724 --> 02:09:00,658
Hi.

1566
02:09:03,362 --> 02:09:05,887
- How was it?
- It was good.

1567
02:09:05,965 --> 02:09:07,899
But I'll tell you something.

1568
02:09:07,967 --> 02:09:11,698
I want us to stay in here
for the rest of the trip.

1569
02:09:16,275 --> 02:09:19,005
Was that Meredith?

1570
02:09:20,513 --> 02:09:22,447
Was who Meredith?

1571
02:09:22,515 --> 02:09:26,246
Meredith Logue. You were kissing someone.
It looked like Meredith.

1572
02:09:32,959 --> 02:09:36,451
I came out to find you.

1573
02:09:36,529 --> 02:09:38,963
Oh, hardly kissing.

1574
02:09:40,366 --> 02:09:43,494
- Kissing off.
- It didn't look that way.

1575
02:09:45,004 --> 02:09:47,029
You know? From a distance?

1576
02:09:52,011 --> 02:09:54,673
I lied... to her.

1577
02:09:55,915 --> 02:09:58,543
<i>She thought she'd seen you.</i>

1578
02:09:58,617 --> 02:10:00,551
Why lie?

1579
02:10:00,619 --> 02:10:05,556
Dickie and Peter together.
That's just too good gossip.

1580
02:10:05,624 --> 02:10:07,558
Or Tom and Peter, even.

1581
02:10:07,626 --> 02:10:10,151
That would be even better gossip.

1582
02:10:10,229 --> 02:10:12,493
Really? Why?

1583
02:10:17,336 --> 02:10:21,773
I-I, um-- I'm completely lost.

1584
02:10:24,443 --> 02:10:26,377
I know.

1585
02:10:27,680 --> 02:10:30,808
I'm sorry, Peter.

1586
02:10:30,883 --> 02:10:32,851
I'm lost.

1587
02:10:35,955 --> 02:10:39,356
I'm gonna be stuck in the basement,
aren't I?

1588
02:10:39,425 --> 02:10:42,724
<i>Aren't I?</i>

1589
02:10:42,795 --> 02:10:44,729
That's my--

1590
02:10:47,833 --> 02:10:49,767
Terrible...

1591
02:10:51,103 --> 02:10:53,196
and alone...

1592
02:10:53,272 --> 02:10:56,708
and dark.

1593
02:10:56,776 --> 02:10:59,472
And I've lied...

1594
02:10:59,545 --> 02:11:02,639
about who I am...

1595
02:11:02,715 --> 02:11:04,706
and where I am.

1596
02:11:04,784 --> 02:11:07,309
Now no one'll ever find me.

1597
02:11:08,888 --> 02:11:11,220
What do you mean,
lied about who you are?

1598
02:11:11,290 --> 02:11:13,952
I always thought it'd be better...

1599
02:11:14,026 --> 02:11:17,120
to be a fake somebody...

1600
02:11:17,196 --> 02:11:20,131
than a real nobody.

1601
02:11:20,199 --> 02:11:23,066
<i>What are you talking about?
You're not a nobody.</i>

1602
02:11:23,135 --> 02:11:25,660
That's the last thing you are.

1603
02:11:33,079 --> 02:11:36,640
<i>Peter.</i>

1604
02:11:36,715 --> 02:11:39,275
Tell me some good things
about Tom Ripley.

1605
02:11:41,187 --> 02:11:43,815
No, don't get up.
Don't get up. Don't get up.

1606
02:11:46,759 --> 02:11:48,693
Just--

1607
02:11:51,497 --> 02:11:55,228
Just tell me some nice things...
about Tom Ripley.

1608
02:11:58,337 --> 02:12:01,397
"Good things about Tom Ripley."

1609
02:12:03,342 --> 02:12:05,537
That could take me some time.

1610
02:12:08,081 --> 02:12:11,949
Tom is talented. Tom is tender.

1611
02:12:13,352 --> 02:12:15,320
Tom is beautiful.

1612
02:12:15,388 --> 02:12:17,822
You're such a liar.

1613
02:12:21,127 --> 02:12:24,528
Tom is-- Tom is a mystery.

1614
02:12:30,103 --> 02:12:32,663
<i>Tom is not a nobody.</i>

1615
02:12:36,275 --> 02:12:40,143
<i>Tom has secrets
he doesn't want to tell me,</i>

1616
02:12:40,213 --> 02:12:42,579
<i>and I wish he would.</i>

1617
02:12:46,752 --> 02:12:49,186
<i>Tom has nightmares.</i>

1618
02:12:53,259 --> 02:12:55,693
<i>That's not a good thing.</i>

1619
02:13:00,299 --> 02:13:02,893
<i>Tom has someone to love him.</i>

1620
02:13:04,470 --> 02:13:06,904
<i>That is a good thing.</i>

1621
02:13:09,742 --> 02:13:14,202
<i>Mmm. Tom is crushing me.</i>

1622
02:13:14,280 --> 02:13:17,647
<i>Tom is crushing me.</i>

1623
02:13:17,717 --> 02:13:21,551
<i>Tom. Tom, you're crush--</i>

1624
02:13:21,621 --> 02:13:24,522
<i>Oh, God!</i>

1625
02:13:24,590 --> 02:13:26,455
<i>Oh, God!</i>

1626
02:13:26,526 --> 02:13:28,460
<i>Oh, God!</i>

1627
02:13:35,635 --> 02:13:38,069
<i>Oh, God! Peter.</i>

1628
02:16:07,286 --> 02:16:09,754
<i>You don't know</i>

1629
02:16:09,822 --> 02:16:15,055
<i>What love is</i>

1630
02:16:15,127 --> 02:16:20,963
<i>Until you know the meaning
of the blues</i>

1631
02:16:23,002 --> 02:16:26,301
<i>Till you love the love</i>

1632
02:16:26,372 --> 02:16:30,536
<i>You had to lose</i>

1633
02:16:30,609 --> 02:16:32,577
<i>You don't know</i>

1634
02:16:32,645 --> 02:16:35,978
<i>What love is</i>

1635
02:16:38,584 --> 02:16:43,988
<i>You don't know how lips hurt</i>

1636
02:16:46,192 --> 02:16:48,319
<i>Until you've kissed</i>

1637
02:16:48,394 --> 02:16:54,026
<i>And had to pay the cost</i>

1638
02:16:54,099 --> 02:16:57,193
<i>Until you've flipped your heart</i>

1639
02:16:57,269 --> 02:17:01,968
<i>And found you've lost</i>

